<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Export Earnings Increased by 23 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Export earnings of Bangladesh
increased by 23 percent during the first month of current fiscal
year (2000-2001), in sharp contrast with the poor export
performance in last several years, a source in the Export
Promotion Bureau (EPB) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The export earnings in July this year amounted to 634 million U.
S. dollars, exceeding the target of 526 million dollars by 20
percent, the official told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Major export earners, ready-made garments, tea, raw jute and
jute goods, chemical products and petroleum products, were among
the items which recorded high growth during this period.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's export growth fell by 8.27 percent during the last
fiscal year, the official said, blaming the decline in export
competitiveness on currency devaluation by South Asian and
Southeast Asian countries following the 1997 financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We had to readjust our currency over the past three years. But
we did that at a slower rate to avoid adverse impact on the
country's import-dependent economy," the EPB source said.
</P>
<P>
Aiming at promoting export and increasing foreign exchange
reserve, the Bangladeshi government has decided in August to
devaluate its currency by six percent from 51 taka against one
dollar to 54 against one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
