<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Needs to Strengthen Missile Capability: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Minister of Defense and
Armed Forces Logistics Ali Shamkhani stressed here on Thursday that
Iran needs to strengthen its missile capability to fight foreign
threats and safeguard national security.
</P>
<P>
Iran faces threats from advanced missile technology, which is
imported mainly from the West, he said at a seminar on aerospace
technology.
</P>
<P>
So Iran has to bid for a strong missile capability to safeguard
national security in face of contingent regional threats and
foreign threats, Shamkhani was quoted by the official Islamic
Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister did not mention which countries are posing threats
to Iran, but he is most likely referring to Israel, Tehran's arch
foe in the region that is militarily backed by the United States.
</P>
<P>
He said Iran does not seek unconventional or offensive weapons,
despite allegations by Washington that Iran seeks to acquire
weapons of mass destruction and poses threats to Gulf countries.
</P>
<P>
The minister claimed that Iran now possesses aerospace
technology and is capable of using the technology in the military
or civilian industries.
</P>
<P>
His remarks echoed those of Navy Commander Rear Admiral Abbas
Mohtaj, who said on Tuesday that Iran's armed forces have achieved
self-sufficiency in military hardware and aerospace technology.
</P>
<P>
Iran has made a lot of missile tests in recent years. In July,
an upgraded Shahab-3 missile, with a range of 1,300 kilometers, was
successfully tested, causing concern in Israel and the U.S..
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
