<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2007 GMT, September 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat have agreed during their Wednesday's talks in New
York to continue making efforts in the coming 24 hours to resume
the stalled Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Nabil Abu-Rudeina, Arafat's political advisor, Thursday told
Voice of Palestine radio that the meeting, held on the sidelines of
the ongoing U.N. Millennium Summit, touched upon U.S. proposals for
breaking the deadlock in the talks. However, no solutions
acceptable to both parties were reached. (Palestine-US-Peace
Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSAELM -- Two elderly people infected with the West Nile
virus died Wednesday night in hospital at Kfar Saba, in the central
part of Israel, bringing to six the number of people who died of
the virus in the past year.
</P>
<P>
West Nile virus, transmitted to humans after they are bitten by
an infected mosquito, can in some instances lead to encephalitis, a
dangerous swelling of the brain. (Israel-West Nile Virus)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has reiterated that
the Arab people will never accept Israeli control of Islamic holy
sites in Jerusalem and that this unanimity will not be compromised,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Arabs are opposed to Israeli sovereignty over religious
symbols in Jerusalem, especially Al-Aqsa mosque, Islam's third
holiest site, and this position was not open for negotiation,
Mubarak told Samir Ragab, editor-in-chief of Al-Gomhuria daily, in
an interview. (Egypt-Israel-Jerusalem)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq reiterated on Thursday that it opposes oil
production increase by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the official Iraqi News Agency (INA),
Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Muhammad Rashid said, "All facts have
confirmed that the quantity of oil is sufficient in meeting the
world demand." (Iraq-OPEC-Oil)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- No dead fish has been found yet on the United Arab
Emirates' (UAE) shore, nor have the country's Coast Guard witnessed
any Red tide these days, reported the official news agency on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But the Dubai Municipality has taken necessary precautionary
measures since finding millions of dead fish near neighboring Omani
shores last week, which was reportedly an ecological phenomenon
that may spread to the eastern shores of the UAE. (UAE-Fish)
</P>
</TEXT>
