<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets U.N. Secretary-General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
met with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan here this morning and
exchanged views with him on the affairs of the United Nations and
other major regional and world issues.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president congratulated the secretary-general on
the successful convening of the U.N. Millennium Summit, hoping
that the leaders of all countries would reach consensus on the
role of the United Nations in world affairs through extensive and
thorough exchange of views.
</P>
<P>
On the role of the United Nations, Jiang said that the United
Nations is the most important international organization in the
world today and it is in the common interests of all member states
to safeguard the purposes and principles of the Charter of the
United Nations and to enhance the U.N. role in world affairs.
</P>
<P>
He expressed China's support for the positive role played by
the United Nations and its Secretary-General in the world affairs.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the question of development, Jiang said that the
rapid development of economic globalization and the booming of
information technology have further widened the gap between the
developing and the developed nations.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is not enough just to solve the poverty of the
developing countries. A good external environment should also be
created for them while offering them funding, technological and
manpower support so as to help them bridge the "digital gap" and
make all the countries enjoying common development and prosperity
in the process of economic globalization, he added.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also briefed Annan on the process of the ratification by
the Chinese Government of the "International Covenant on Economic,
Social and Cultural Rights", saying that since the signing of the
covenant in 1997, the Chinese Government has done an enormous work
in studies and preparations.
</P>
<P>
The consideration of the covenant is now underway in the
Standing Committee of China's National People's Congress, said
Jiang, who expressed his hope the covenant would be approved as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that he listened earnestly to the speech Jiang
delivered at the U.N. Millennium Summit and expressed his thanks
and appreciation for China's consistent support for the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general, hoping that China would continue to play
its constructive role in world affairs, spoke highly of China's
policy towards Africa and wished success to the Sino-African forum
on cooperation slated for October in Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
