<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Spouses Gather for Teach-in on Girls' Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The spouses of some 70
heads of state or government attending the current Millennium
Summit gathered here Thursday to exchange information, share
experience and draw attention to the gender gap that leaves
millions of girls out of school around the world.
</P>
<P>
Nane Annan, wife of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, was the
honorary chair of the gathering, organized by the United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF). She opened the meeting, which also
included Cherie Blair, wife of the British prime minister, Stella
Obasanjo, wife of the Nigerian president, and some 70 other first
spouses.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF Executive Director Carol Bellamy, who moderated an open
discussion among the participating first spouses, said their forum
focused on two major issues that often keep girls out of school:
concerns about their personal safety and the impact of child labor.
</P>
<P>
"The basic rights of women and girls are violated or ignored at
many points in their lives," Bellamy said prior to the meeting. "
But when a girl is deprived of an education, her entire trajectory
through life is diminished -- her health, her income, her
opportunities. That is unacceptable -- and it is completely
correctable. That's what this forum is about, and it is
outstanding that so many spouses of world leaders are taking this
issue personally."
</P>
<P>
Bellamy said that girls' education -- a top priority for UNICEF
-- is an essential element in the healthy development of any
society. She said that educated women tend to be healthier, raise
healthier families and have better-educated children than women
without the benefit of schooling.
</P>
<P>
Educated women are also better able to protect and support
themselves, their families and their children. They are more
productive at home and better paid in the workplace, she said.
</P>
<P>
"The social and economic benefits of educating girls have been
documented in country after country, and boys as well as girls
benefit when educational systems are free of gender bias," Bellamy
said.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF is a leading U.N. agency supporting the Girls' Education
Initiative, launched by the U.N. secretary-general at the World
Education Forum in Dakar, capital of Senegal, in April 2000.
</P>
<P>
Education for girls is also a priority issue in the secretary-
general's Millennium Report and is on the agenda for the
Millennium Summit, which began Wednesday at the U.N. headquarters
in New York.
</P>
<P>
In his report, the U.N. chief urged the world leaders, who are
at the three-day summit, to reduce the gender gap in education by
2005 and to ensure that all children, regardless of gender, are
getting a quality basic education by 2015.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF, the only U.N. organization dedicated exclusively to
children, works for child protection, survival and development
within the framework of the Convention on the Rights of the Child.
</P>
<P>
Created by the United Nations General Assembly in 1946 to meet
the emergency needs of children in post-war Europe, UNICEF now
supports programs aimed at improving the lives of children
everywhere, particularly those in developing countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
