<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Security Council Meets at Heads of State Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A meeting of the United
Nations Security Council at the heads of state level was held here
Thursday with the focus on peacekeeping issues, especially in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The security council summit considered a report issued in late
August by a special U.N. panel which was set up by the U.N.
secretary-general to consider how to strengthen peace operations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said, "To say that the eyes of the world are upon you is
both to say too little and to much."
</P>
<P>
"Too little, because the fate of future generations could be
affected by the decisions of this security council summit. Too
much, because many in the present generation are losing confidence
in the ability of the United Nations to make the difference
between war and peace," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"This contradiction reflects a crisis of credibility facing
this council and this organization in discharging its gravest
responsibility: the maintenance of peace and security," the U.N.
chief said.
</P>
<P>
"Too many vulnerable communities in too many regions of the
world now hesitate to look to the United Nations to assist them in
their hour of need," he said.
</P>
<P>
"No amount of resolutions or statements can change this reality.
Only actions can: prompt, united and effective action, pursued
with skills and discipline to halt conflict and restore the peace.
Only such determined action can restore the reputation of the
United Nations as a credible force for peace and justice," he
added.
</P>
<P>
A declaration was adopted by the end of the summit in which the
council pledged to uphold the purposes and principles of the
Charter of the United Nations and reaffirmed its commitment to the
principles of sovereign equality, national sovereignty,
territorial integrity and political independence of all states.
</P>
<P>
The council also reaffirmed the importance of adhering to the
principles of the non-threat or non-use of force in international
relations in any manner inconsistent with the purposes of the
United Nations, and of peaceful settlement of international
disputes.
</P>
<P>
The security council comprises five permanent members and ten
nonpermanent members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
