<HEADLINE> Russian Oil Exports Up 4 Percent in January-July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Russia's crude oil exports in
January-July increased by 3.068 million tons or 4 percent to 76.
479 million tons from one year earlier, the Russian customs
authorities said in a report Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Revenue from oil exports in the first seven months mounted to
13.198 billion U.S. dollars, up 7.723 billion dollars or 120
percent from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
In January-July, Russia exported 74.525 million tons of oil,
worth 12.94 billion dollars, to non-CIS (Commonwealth of
Independent States) countries, and 1.95 million tons, worth 257.6
million dollars, to CIS states.
</P>
<P>
The largest supplies were to Germany (11.71 million tons) and
Poland (10.139 million tons), according to the report.
</P>
<P>
In the single month of July, the exports rose to 12.21 million
tons (2.033 billion dollars), of which 11.83 million tons (1.978
billion dollars) were to countries outside the CIS and 379,980
tons (54.59 million dollars) to the CIS.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Russia exported a total of 123.9 million tons of oil,
worth 13.333 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to another report by the Russian Energy Ministry, the
country produced over 212 million tons of oil in the first eight
months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Oil exports outside the CIS since the start of the year reached
93.09 million tons, including 12.14 million tons in August, while
the supplies to the CIS nations jumped to 385,800 tons in January-
August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
