<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conditions Are Not Ripe for Talks With U.S., Iran Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Khatami, on his second visit to New York to attend the United
Nations General Assembly session, told a press conference that
there had been some positive developments in relations but the
United States must do more to make amendments for past wrongs
against Iran.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Iranian president renewed demands for an apology
for the U.S. role in a 1953 coup that overthrew Iranian Prime
Minister Mohammad Mossadeq despite U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright's acknowledgment in April of U.S.
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
"Contacts between the people of Iran and the United States have
been positive," he said. "Relations are not only based on pure
misunderstanding. There are some positive elements."
</P>
<P>
Khatami was in New York to attend the three-day Millennium
Summit, which kicked off here Wednesday. U.S. President Bill
Clinton is also in New York and on Wednesday the leaders of Iran
and the United States listened to each other's speeches at the
summit.
</P>
<P>
The mere presence of both presidents at the United Nations
headquarters in New York sparked the possibility of an encounter,
even by coincidence. But Khatami indicated that any such meeting
would be premature because Iran still had "serious issues" with
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said a meeting between Iranian parliament speaker Mehdi
Karroubi and U.S. lawmakers in New York last week had been an
unplanned encounter and did not presage talks between the two
governments.
</P>
<P>
"For a president to meet officially with officials of another
country, the political and historical setting has to be available,
" he said. "Unfortunately, such settings are not yet available
between our countries."
</P>
<P>
Among the obstacles, Khatami listed U.S. unilateral trade
sanctions, U.S. opposition to building pipelines to carry Caspian
oil and gas exports across Iranian territory and what he called "
animosities and allegations" against Iran.
</P>
<P>
"We need apologies for that as well as some practical measures
and steps that prove that in reality that (U.S.) behavior has
changed," he said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. legislation punishing oil companies that invest in Iran's
energy sector is due to expire next year unless the U.S. Congress
renews it.
</P>
<P>
Iran severed diplomatic relations with the United States in
April 1980, and there have been signs of improvement on the
bilateral ties since Khatami came to power in August 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
