<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The European Union (EU) has donated 1.5 million doses
of vaccines to Turkey to counter the foot-and-mouth disease among
cattle in western Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of the vaccines arrived in Turkey on Wednesday
and the second batch will be carried in soon.
</P>
<P>
The Representation of the European Commission to Turkey said in
a statement that the commission had immediately offered the
vaccines as soon as it learned of the outbreak of foot-and-mouth
disease in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The visiting Director General of Development Aid
Department of the Japan Bank for International Cooperation (JBIC),
Shozo Kitta, said on Wednesday the bank would continue to support
Turkey's development projects.
</P>
<P>
Kitta, who is heading a JBIC delegation, told reporters the bank
is financing three important projects in Turkey with a total cost
of 1 billion U.S. dollars. These projects are Istanbul Water Supply
Project, Bozuyuk-Mekece Road Development Project and the Bosphorus
Strait Tube Tunnel Project.
</P>
<P>
The JBIC delegation, which came to Turkey on a fact-finding
mission, has held talks with Odd Per, representative of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) to Turkey, and Ajay Chhibbed,
Turkey director of the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The EU has made it clear that it would not extend any
assistance to Turkey's controversial nuclear energy plant.
</P>
<P>
The European Parliament has asked Turkey to exclude nuclear
energy projects from the regulations which define economic and
social aid.
</P>
<P>
A report prepared by French deputy Philippe Morillon noted that
Turkey was located on an earthquake zone and said that a nuclear
power plant might cause a nuclear disaster which would spread to
the entire region.
</P>
<P>
OMAN -- Israeli exports to Arab nations were estimated at 101
million dollars in 1999.
</P>
<P>
This figure includes direct trade dealings with some Arab
countries and illegal ones with some quarters in Arab nations which
still boycott Israeli products, the Association of Israeli Plant
Owners said.
</P>
<P>
Israel has declared official relations with Jordan, Egypt, the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) and Mauritania and established
trade bonds with Qatar, Oman and Tunisia via representative offices
in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Yet, other Arab nations are averse to any sort of trade exchange
with Israel unless it withdraws from all occupied Arab territories.
</P>
</TEXT>
