<HEADLINE> Hariri Vows to Develop Economic Ties With Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese ex-premier Rafik
Hariri, who is most likely to recapture the portfolio, said on
Thursday that Lebanon should expedite economic relations with
Syria.
</P>
<P>
Hariri made the remarks in a banquet to celebrate the victory of
his "Dignity Group" in the just-concluded parliament elections. The
group swept off 18 seats in 19 quotas in the elite Beirut
electorate.
</P>
<P>
"The new Syrian authority has opened a mass market and many
opportunities for us that we can benefit from with our Syrian
brothers," Hariri said, adding,"We can see it clearly from (Syrian
President) Bashar al-Assad's statement when he was sworn in that
the new authority is keen to open up towards outsides."
</P>
<P>
He expressed his dissatisfaction towards the current economic
ties between the two countries. "We see a good political relation
and enjoy a good security relation. We should also have a
satisfactory economic one," he announced.
</P>
<P>
Hariri added that Lebanon will be the first country that can be
affected by the opening wave from Syria. "Our two countries should
work together so as to benefit from the markets and productions,"
the billionaire politician stressed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hariri, who is the hottest candidate for the
premiership, said the new government should be a solidary one to
address those challenges in the future.
</P>
<P>
The ex-premier, who served from 1992-1998, elaborated that the
economic problems are linked with political and social
situations. "To cure the economic crisis we should not focus
our attention on the economic policies. The crisis is a result of
all domestic and foreign policies," he said, adding, "We have to
form a united government to save Lebanon, to save our people."
</P>
<P>
Lebanon is experiencing the harshest economic depression in
three decades. Partly, the crisis helped Hariri defeat his rival,
sitting Prime Minister Salim Hoss who lost his deputy seat in the
election. 
