<HEADLINE> French, British Experts Confirm Objective of Letting Concorde Fly Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- French and British aviation
officials and experts Thursday confirmed their objective of
finding a solution to let the Concorde supersonic aircraft fly
again.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting held at the headquarters of General Direction
of Civil Aviation (DGAC) here, the working group of French and
British experts studied the primary report submitted by the French
Bureau of Accident Investigation (BEA) on the July 25 Concorde
crash in which 113 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft builders are concentrating their investigation on
possible tire explosion, fuel tank leakage and origin of fire,
said DGAC.
</P>
<P>
French Minister of Transport Jean-Claude Gayssot said on
Wednesday that he thought Concorde should be allowed to fly again
in future.
</P>
<P>
France and Britain have permanently suspended the airworthiness
certificate of Concorde after the July 25 crash near Paris.
</P>
<P>
Primary investigation showed that the crash could be caused by
the cutting of the tire on the undercarriage by a metal strip on
the runway.
</P>
<P>
The explosion of one or two tires then led to the damage of
fuel tanks, the leaking of oil, and the outbreak of a fire.
</P>
