<HEADLINE> France Urges Priorities of Action to Eradicate Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- France stressed here
Thursday that priorities of action must be set so as to pull
billions of people out of abject poverty.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to a roundtable of heads of state or government,
French President Jacques Chirac, who is here attending the U.N.
Millennium Summit which opened at the U.N. headquarters in New
York Wednesday, said there are more than 800 million people who
are still hungry and 1.2 billion people are living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
Half of humankind is living on less than 2 dollars a day and
suffering from the succession of ills that exacerbate the
precariousness of their situation: illiteracy, unemployment,
unhealthy housing, lacking of hygiene and health care, Chirac said.
</P>
<P>
Priorities of action must be set, including increasing official
development assistance, accelerating debt relief for the heavily
indebted poor countries, starting a new round of global trade
talks to make trade more compliant with rules and intensifying the
fight against major diseases, the president said.
</P>
<P>
Increasing official development assistance is crucial for
promoting the establishment of institutions for good governance,
fostering environmentally sensitive economic development and
developing social programs to reduce poverty through technology
transfers and technical assistance, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He added that assistance is particularly necessary for the
poorest countries and is absolutely necessary to enable them to
build the social and economic infrastructures they need to break
out of the vicious cycle of isolation, illiteracy and disease.
</P>
<P>
The three-day summit, which is the largest-ever gathering of
world leaders in the U.N. history, is convened under the official
theme "The United Nations in the 21st Century."
</P>
<P>
In addition to make formal speeches at the summit, the world
leaders also participate in one of four interactive roundtables.
</P>
</TEXT>
