<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EP Slams British Call for Human Embryo Cloning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Parliament on
Thursday slammed a call by Britain's chief medical officer to
allow British scientists to clone human embryos for use in medical
research.
</P>
<P>
The parliament, the legislative body of the European Union,
passed a non-binding resolution that says that therapeutical
cloning for medical research irreversibly crosses a boundary in
research norms and that no EU money should be used to fund such
research.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was passed with 237 votes for and 230 votes
against in Strasbourg.
</P>
<P>
Philippe Busquin, EU research commissioner, said that EU rules
already have excluded spending research cash on human cloning for
either reproductive or therapeutical purposes.
</P>
<P>
The British government's chief medical officer Liam Donaldson
recommended in August that the country's scientists be allowed to
clone human embryos for use in a wider range of medical research.
</P>
<P>
The British parliament in 1990 approved embryo research for
infertility and genetic disorder treatments.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the chief of the 15-nation European Union expressed
his support for a debate on the sensitive topic of therapeutical
cloning.
</P>
<P>
Romano Prodi said that an equilibrium could be struck through
the debate between ethical concerns and commercial benefits of
therapeutical cloning.
</P>
<P>
The union's fifth Framework Program for Research and Technology
Development from 1998 to 2002 excludes financial support for any
research projects concerning the cloning of human embryos for the
purpose of reproduction.
</P>
<P>
Therapeutical cloning involves two basic techniques -- cellular
therapy and formation of embryos via cloning.
</P>
<P>
Cellular therapy has been used for several years already to
cure such diseases as leukemia and it aims at replacing diseased
human cells or at increasing insufficient cells in human bodies.
</P>
<P>
This therapy also has a prospect of being able to cure
degenerative diseases such as the Alzheimer and Parkinson
syndromes.
</P>
<P>
Yet the cellular therapy has displayed an inefficiency in
dealing with such problems as incompatible immunology, lack of
transplant organs and absence of graftable cells for several types
of human tissues.
</P>
<P>
Therapeutical cloning is expected to be able to cope with these
problems.
</P>
<P>
The therapeutical cloning will replace the nucleus of ovum with
a cell taken from the patient to be treated and the embryo thus
created will only be used to provide the cells that will later be
transplanted back onto the patient in question. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
