<HEADLINE> Belgium to Auction UMTS Licenses in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Belgium is set to auction
four UMTS licenses in December to follow suit as Britain, the
Netherlands and Germany did to upgrade their mobile telephone
systems.
</P>
<P>
The licenses will allow the winning bidders to provide high-
speed mobile telecommunications service in the next 20 years but
what qualification terms companies have to meet to be able to take
part in the auction were not yet announced.
</P>
<P>
A spokesperson from the Belgian telecommunications ministry
only said that the Belgian auction of UMTS licenses would be
organized the same way as in Britain and Germany.
</P>
<P>
The ministry did not disclose what the expected auction
proceeds would be.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands, that expected to net a huge amount of money
from UMTS auctions, ended up only getting 6 billion Dutch guilders
(2.6 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
UMTS stands for universal mobile telecommunications standard,
the latest generation of cellular phone service. UMTS boasts of a
transmission speed 40 times faster than that of the existing GSM
standard.
</P>
<P>
The higher telecommunication speed makes possible new
capabilities such as mobile phone connection to the Internet and
video displays.
</P>
<P>
Britain was the first European Union country to have auctioned
UMTS licenses. In April, the British government got 22.5 billion
pounds (34 billion U.S. dollars) from the auction sales of five
UMTS licenses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
