<HEADLINE> Euro Keeps Hitting New Lows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The euro plunged on Thursday
to its lowest level in its 20-month life against the U.S. dollar
as confidence in the single currency was further dented by
conflicting comments from EU officials
</P>
<P>
The single currency once fell to 86.35 cents against the dollar,
crushing the previous day's low of 86.85 cents.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder had
played a leading role in the euro's plunge in the past three days
after he said that he was not concerned about the euro's weakness
and after his office repeated his lack of concern.
</P>
<P>
The German finance ministry, however, on Thursday tried to prop
up the euro by saying that Germany was "eminently interested" in a
strong euro and German and French finance ministers said the euro
zone finance ministers were meeting on Friday and were expected to
issue a statement concerning the euro.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the European
Union, said that the current exchange rate against the dollar was
not appropriate.
</P>
<P>
The European Central Bank's silence on the latest fall of the
euro was also blamed by analysts who said that the bank's silence
and the conflicting comments by European leaders only left the
single currency at the mercy of speculative attacks.
</P>
<P>
The European Central Bank has consistently warned that a weak
euro is fueling inflation in the 15-nation bloc in that it makes
imports relatively more expensive.
</P>
<P>
The bank has just raised its benchmark lending interest rate by
a quarter point on August 31 to help bolster the weakening
currency. Raising interest rates is usually a move that tends to
bolster local currency.
</P>
<P>
The euro was launched on January 1, 1999, at a value of 1.18
dollars and now it has devalued by more than a quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
