<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Reduce Troops by 400,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Russia will reduce its armed
forces and other military servicemen by 400,000 by the end of 2003,
the Interfax news agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The reduction will start in 2001 and the main steps are to be
completed by 2003. It is planned that Russia's armed forces will
have been reduced by 350,000 servicemen by that time and will
total 850,000, Interfax cited "reliable sources in Moscow" as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Land Forces will decrease by almost 180,000 servicemen, the
Navy by over 50,000 and the Air Force by about 40,000, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The personnel of other power structures will also be greatly
reduced, the sources said. The internal troops of the Russian
Interior Ministry are expected to be reduced by over 20,000. The
number of railway troops will be reduced by 10,000 and the Federal
Border Guard Service will be reduced by 5,000.
</P>
<P>
Other ministries and agencies that have military formations
will be reduced by a total of over 25,000 people, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
In all, the Russian armed forces and other power structures
will cut down their staff by about 400,000.
</P>
<P>
Serious reorganization will also be carried out in the
administration of the Defense Ministry and rear structures,
including military medicine.
</P>
<P>
"Radical reduction is also expected in the Strategic Missile
Force, which will see a reduction of some 10 missile divisions by
2006," the sources said. The space missile defense troops and the
space military forces will be taken out of this branch of service
in 2001 and will be put under the control of the Russian General
Staff, they said.
</P>
<P>
The Strategic Missile Force is expected to be transformed into
an independent arm of service in 2002, and later, approximately in
2006, to be included in the Russian Air Force, they said.
</P>
<P>
Such a radical reduction is planned because the state cannot
adequately finance the structures, they said.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry, the General Staff, the Finance Ministry
and the Ministry for Industry, Science and Technologies, which is
in charge of issues relating to state defense orders, are
currently calculating how much funding will be required for the
planned reforms.
</P>
<P>
Next year, funding for defense expenditures will mainly be
spent on planned reforms, research and design work as well as on
upgrading and repairs of military technology. It is not planned to
purchase large batches of new samples of weapons and military
technology, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The final decision has not yet been made "at the highest
political level," where the final parameters of reduction will be
determined, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
