<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The half-month second stage of the Egyptian annual
summer sale started Wednesday, involving 5,000 public and private
shops and enterprises, an official with the Ministry of Supply and
Domestic Trade said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Violations of sale regulations in the first stage reached 650,
the Arabic Al-Alam Al-Youm quoted the official as saying. Intensive
crackdowns have been launched against the department stores which
offer expired or bad commodities, added the official.
</P>
<P>
MASCAT -- Oman will invest 2.65 billion Omani riyals (about 7
billion U.S. dollars) in industry during the next 10 years as part
of efforts to diversify investment that had been focused on energy,
an official at the Omani Ministry of Trade and Industry has said.
</P>
<P>
Oman will gradually turn from a country depending on energy and
foreign labor into one relying on industry and local manpower,
added the official. Foreign workers constitutes 25 percent of
Oman's 2.3 million population.
</P>
<P>
As a small oil-producer, Oman is not a member of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) and produces
900,000 barrels of oil per day. Oil and gas earnings accounted for
70 percent of its national income in 1999.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey and Czech Republic signed an agreement of
cooperation on agriculture and food industry in Prague on Thursday,
reported the Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The pact was signed by Turkish Minister of Agriculture and Rural
Affairs Husnu Yusuf Gokalp and his Czech counterpart Jan Fencl.
</P>
<P>
Gokalp said that Turkey and Czech Republic, besides advancing
cooperation in agriculture, should also support each other's EU
candidacy policies.
</P>
<P>
"As two EU candidates, we should form a cooperation platform
between our two countries to make good use of the EU candidacy
process. Turkey and the Czech Republic should support each other's
candidacy to the EU and also they should benefit from each other's
experiences," said Fencl.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey and Yemen signed a series of cooperation
agreements in Ankara on Thursday, reported the Anatolia News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
The accords, which were signed by Turkish State Minister Ramazan
Miraoglu and Yemeni Trade and Supply Minister Abdullaziz Al Kymain,
cover highway transportation, cooperation in tourism and
encouragement of investments.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a memorandum of understanding was signed by Mehmet
Guler, director general and president of the Executive Board of the
Anatolia News Agency, and the Yemeni minister, on behalf of Yemeni
News Agency, which foresees cooperation between the news agencies
of two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
