<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Opposes OPEC Oil Output Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Iraq reiterated on Thursday
that it opposes oil production increase by the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the official Iraqi News Agency (INA),
Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Muhammad Rashid said, "All facts have
confirmed that the quantity of oil is sufficient in meeting the
world demand."
</P>
<P>
Rashid said that to keep the international oil market stable and
protect the interests of OPEC member states, Iraq rejects the
pressure exerted on OPEC members by the United States who aims at "
overflowing the market with the Saudi oil," the INA said.
</P>
<P>
The recent decision by Saudi Arabia to increase oil production
by 600 thousand barrels a day "constitutes a challenge and
violation of OPEC regulations," Rashid said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq regarded that the "surprising" move by Saudi Arabia, a key
U.S. ally in the Middle East, came under the U.S. pressure to push
down oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi minister urged the upcoming OPEC oil ministers meeting
to adopt a stance that is "capable of reflecting OPEC member
states' interests."
</P>
<P>
As to the appointment of a new OPEC secretary general to succeed
outgoing Rilwanu Lukman, Rashid stressed that Lukman's successor
should be able to resist external pressure, especially that from
the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Iraq deems that Abdul Ameer Al-Nbari, the former Iraqi envoy to
the United Nations, is "a suitable and efficient person" to assume
the job, Rashid said.
</P>
<P>
Rashid will lead an Iraqi delegation to attend the oil ministers
meeting due to be held in the Austrian capital Vienna on September
10.
</P>
<P>
OPEC is expected to make the decision to increase its daily
production by another half million barrels a day at the meeting.
The world's largest oil cartel has increased its oil output by 2.4
million barrels a day this year.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices reached a 10-year record high of 32.85 U.S. dollars a
barrel on Monday, while benchmark Brent crude for October traded at
a new high of 32.88 dollars on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and the European Union have been pressuring OPEC in
raising oil production to cool down the oil prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
