<HEADLINE> Israeli Minister Raps 3 Policemen for Abusing Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Public Security
Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami Thursday blasted three Israeli border
policemen for allegedly beating and abusing Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"This is a very serious matter," Ben-Ami, who now also
temporarily holds the foreign ministry portfolio, said in an
interview with Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
The three policemen reportedly stopped a car with three
Palestinians and later beat them with fists and rocks at a
roadblock between Jerusalem and Abu Dis, an Arab town on the
outskirts of Jerusalem, on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
They also reportedly made the three Palestinians lie on the
ground, stepped on their throats, and pointed guns at them for
posing for camera.
</P>
<P>
With the aid of human right groups, the Palestinian victims
filed a complaint to Israeli police over the matter, which led to
the arrest of the three policemen on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The three suspects will be brought before a judge Thursday
evening with a request to remand them in custody until trial,
according to Border Police spokesman Peretz Razon.
</P>
<P>
It was announced that the Justice Ministry's Police
Investigation Unit will help determine whether to press charges
against them.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami warned that the police investigation unit should not be
used as an alibi. "We can't have people apparently acting like
animals and then say 'OK, the police investigation unit will deal
with it,' thus alleviating ourselves of our command
responsibility," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also ordered a series of discipline measures to prevent
such "ugly things" from happening again in the future, including a
plan to introduce behavior refresher courses to all members of the
Border Police.
</P>
<P>
The Border Police is the elite task force in the police
infrastructure, dealing mainly with internal security problems and
fighting against terrorists.
</P>
<P>
According to Ha'aretz daily's website, one suspect told its
reporters before Thursday evening's hearing: "What we did is not
special. Everybody (in the unit) does it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
