<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Tries Hard to Encourage Students Study Hi-Tech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli Council for
Higher Education on Thursday agreed on a plan to encourage more
students in Israel to study hi-tech by promising bright job
opportunities and lucrative scholarships.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after the council, which has proposed a
series of emergency measures to attract hi-tech staff and students,
met with hi-tech leaders on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, each student who studies for a master's degree
in hi-tech will be granted a scholarship of 50,000 shekels (about
12,500 U.S. dollars) and for a doctorate, 60,000 shekels (15,000
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The move is intended to address the acute shortage of hi-tech
engineers and computer programers in Israel, which is rated the
fastest developing country in the hi-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
The growth pace of the Israeli hi-tech industry, which employs
some 60,000 people, is however hindered by a lack of about 10,000
skilled workers.
</P>
<P>
The plan tabled by the Council of Higher Education also allows
full-time faculty members from universities to work one or two days
a week in hi-tech firms. They will be entitled to accept the
attractive compensation packages offered in the hi-tech sector,
including stock options.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, suitable hi-tech personnel are also encouraged
to take academic posts in universities in addition to their regular
jobs. They would continue to draw their full salary from their
companies, in addition to getting paid by the academic institution
they teach.
</P>
<P>
As the hi-tech industry has become probably the most lucrative
and promising field in Israel, there is also an increasing number
of students graduating with degrees in computer science and
electrical engineering.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, there were 2,000 graduates in these hi-tech fields. The
number, according to a prediction of the council, would reach 5,000
when students of the class of 2002 graduate. The increase of
students further creates a shortage of faculty members in computer
science and electrical engineering.
</P>
<P>
Israel's hi-tech industry contributes half the growth figures
for the economy. Israel's growth rate in 2000 is expected to be 4.4
percent. Without hi-tech, however, this would have been only 2.4
percent, according to a think tank paper presented to the Israeli
parliament at the end of July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
