<HEADLINE> At Least Two Killed by Landslide in Angola's Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- At least two people have been
killed by an unexpected landslide taking place in a densely
populated suburb of Luanda, the capital of Angola, the official
news agency Angop reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The landslide destroyed a house which was used as a "video club
" for low income people. At least 15 people were inside the house
when the tragedy occurred Wednesday evening, eyewitnesses was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Firemen went to the scene of the disaster immediately and
removed the dead bodies of two youngsters, while more people are
believed to be still under the mass of earth.
</P>
<P>
The area where the earth fall occurred has been under a Luanda
government's construction ban since 1990, but many people, mostly
war displaced persons from inland provinces, ignored the
prohibition and settled themselves there in shanty houses.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the population of the Angolan capital
has increased by 53 percent from 2.3 million in 1995 to 3.5
million in early 2000, mainly due to the augment of the war-
displaced population.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, there are some 3.7 million displaced persons in
the southwest African country as a result of a 26-year civil
conflict between the government and the rebel National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
