<HEADLINE> Guinea-Bissau Coalition Government Falls Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Guinea-Bissau President Kumba
Iala issued a decree Wednesday to exonerate all the government
members of the Resistance of Guinea-Bissau (RGB), one of the two
parties forming the coalition government, Jornal de Angola
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
RGB has been the second largest party of the country since the
general elections held last November, during which Iala became the
president. RGB, united with the Social Renovation Party (PRS) led
by Iala, gained a relative majority in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
After some divergences, the RGB leadership wrote a letter to
Iala on Wednesday, saying that the accord on coalition signed by
the two parties has not been observed.
</P>
<P>
As response, Iala issued the decree, which in practice
announced the collapse of the coalition government.
</P>
<P>
The ruling PRS has to opt between the establishment of a
minority government or soliciting support from the third largest
party of the country, the African Party of Independence of Guinea
and Cape Verde, until October when the next session of the
parliament will be held. 
</P>
