<HEADLINE> Clinton Says No New Mideast Meetings Scheduled Yet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Thursday that no new meetings as yet were scheduled with
Israeli and Palestinian leaders after his talks with them on
Wednesday evening failed to achieve a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
Clinton did not rule out further meetings with the two leaders
this week but said Thursday that there has been no discussion of
another three-way summit to break the impasse in the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, talking to reporters before his private meeting with
South Korean President Kim Dae-jung, said that his talks with
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat went well.
</P>
<P>
"They both very much want an agreement and they understand they
have a limited time in which to achieve it. And we discussed a
whole range of things in terms of where we were and where we are
going," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he was planning another Camp David-style summit with
the Palestinian and Israeli leaders before the end of October,
Clinton said, "There's been no discussion of that."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said Dennis Ross, the senior U.S. mediator on the
Middle East, was holding separate meetings Thursday with Israeli
and Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, Clinton met with Crown Prince Abdullah of
Saudi Arabia and told him that oil prices are "too high" and urged
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) to take
appropriate action.
</P>
<P>
"I told him that I was very concerned that the price of oil was
too high, not just for America but for the world, that if it was
to cause a recession in any part of the world that would hurt the
oil-producing countries," Clinton said during a picture-taking
session with South Korean President Kim Dae-jung.
</P>
<P>
Clinton met Abdullah on Wednesday night at his hotel in
downtown New York. He said he urged OPEC to take "appropriate
action" at its upcoming meeting along the lines of a previous
commitment to increase output to bring down the price of oil.
</P>
