<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protests Against Fuel Price Rise Escalate in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The protest against fuel price
rise by truckers, farmers and taxi drivers is escalating in France
as two national railway services were interrupted on Thursday with
many road blockades set up by protesters.
</P>
<P>
The railway service between Paris and the eastern city of
Strasbourg was interrupted Thursday morning due to blockade by
farmers, said the state railway company SNCF.
</P>
<P>
The high-speed bullet train between the southwestern city of
Bordeaux and the south-central city of Toulouse was also stopped
for the better part of the day by farmers who set up blocks on the
railway track.
</P>
<P>
In the western region of Brittany, protesters blocked roads
around several cities, while farmers and truckers set up blockades
on the French-Belgian border to prevent trucks transporting fuel
from entering France.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission Thursday issued a warning against the
French government calling for the guarantee of free traffic and
free circulation of merchandises in Europe which is being
threatened by the blockades.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, about 100 oil storehouses and refineries are still
being blocked by truckers, resulting in a nationwide shortage of
oil supply.
</P>
<P>
French Interior Minister Daniel Vaillant said the moment has
come for the protesters to lift the blockades as the French people
cannot live in a state of siege indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
The French Defense Ministry said that there is "tension" on the
oil stocks of the armed forces although "all the operational
priorities are preserved" for the time being. 
</P>
</TEXT>
