<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Ready to Back Regional Development: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Post-Cold War developments in
the Caucasus, Central Asia and Balkan that border Turkey have
brought a new vision to Ankara's foreign policy, Turkish State
Minister Abdulhaluk Cay said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cay made the remark in meeting with Donald Johnston, secretary
general of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development(OECD), Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Johnston arrived in Istanbul, Turkish biggest city, Wednesday to
attend a conference on the regional development hosted by the
Istanbul Development of Private Sector Center (IDPS).
</P>
<P>
Cay said that Turkey is located as a bridge between Europe and
Asia, the Caspian and Mediterranean basins and the unique geography
offers a natural opportunity to develop various regional economic
relations.
</P>
<P>
"The representatives and policy-makers from the private sector
who participate in the activities at the Istanbul Development of
Private Sector Center, have an opportunity to get to know each
other's systems and economies," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said it is important for these countries in the Balkan,
Central Asia and Caucasus to strengthen their independence,
mobilize their economic resources, integrate themselves with global
economy to realize prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Turkey was willing to help these countries in their efforts to
the development process, he said.
</P>
<P>
He made an introduction of the activities of Turkish Cooperation
and Development Agency (TIKA), saying that the development of the
private sector in the regions would offer new business
opportunities to businessmen.
</P>
<P>
He said that the IDPS has become "an important international
platform" capable of providing information about the economic
activities in the regions through the help of international
organizations such as the OECD.
</P>
<P>
Cay asked Johnston to give more participation right to Turkish
educators in the OECD's programs, and to help the coordination of
TIKA and OECD in determining the participants and the countries
which are offered service.
</P>
<P>
He also called for the OECD to give Turkey more service at a
lower cost and focus more on studies aimed at finding out the needs
of the countries in the regions.
</P>
<P>
Johnston hailed the center in Istanbul as playing a vital role
in providing support for the development of the countries in the
region, saying that Turkey's support for the OECD was very
important.
</P>
<P>
"It is significant that the center is located in Turkey and it
shares its activities with the countries in the regions," urging
the center to increase activities in promoting the regional
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
