<HEADLINE> S.Lankan President Extends Emergency in Run-up to General Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga has extended a nationwide state of emergency by a
month in the run-up to the October 10 general elections,
government officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, the presidential proclamation on the state of
emergency has to be approved by the parliament which was dissolved
on August 18.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, President Kumaratunga directed the secretary-
general of the parliament to convene a day-long special session of
the parliament on September 14 to seek its approval on the
president's decision, said the officials.
</P>
<P>
During the session, the government will move a resolution
seeking the extension of emergency in the country, an exercise
undertaken every month for the past decade.
</P>
<P>
The parliament would dissolve again after the special session,
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The emergency regulations lend wide ranging powers to the
police and armed forces to arrest and detain suspected Tamil Tiger
rebels who are fighting for a separate state for minority Tamils
in Sri Lanka's north and east since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The emergency, which was first imposed in May 1983, has
continuously been used by each successive government, sometimes in
certain areas and at other times to include the entire nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
