<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourist Arrivals in Nepal Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Tourist arrivals in Nepal
continue to decline even after the resumption of India Airlines
flights to the country on June 1 this year, according to Tribhuvan
International Airport Immigration Office.
</P>
<P>
The data by the immigration office, available on Thursday,
reveals that tourist arrivals into the country in the first eight
months of this year has declined by 13.69 percent as compared to
the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
The total number of tourists that visited Nepal via air till
the end of August stands at 215,000, while the number in the same
period last year was 249,000, the data said.
</P>
<P>
Tourists visiting Nepal through air constitute almost 86
percent of the total tourist arrivals.
</P>
<P>
The hijacking of an Indian Airlines passenger plane on December
24, 1999, en route from Kathmandu to New Delhi prompted the
airlines to suspend all the flights to Nepal for over five months,
which not only affected the number of Indian tourists to Nepal but
also affected tourist arrivals from other countries, as 20 percent
of them come via India.
</P>
<P>
The hijacking episode resulted in a fall of Indian tourist
arrivals by 35.49 percent in the first eight months of this year,
said the data. Indian tourists occupy about 35 percent of tourists
visiting Nepal.
</P>
<P>
However, Nepali tourism entrepreneurs believe that with more
international airlines increasing their flights to Nepal in the
recent months, the tourist arrivals are likely to rise in Winter,
which is the high season for traveling in Nepal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
