<HEADLINE> India Appeals OPEC to Lower Oil Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"I have already sent a communication to all Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) expressing the concern of
India about the alarming rise in prices while requesting them to
take appropriate decisions to reduce prices in their meeting on
September 10," Indian Petroleum Minister Ram Naik was quoted as
saying by the PTI.
</P>
<P>
Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee, who left here late
Wednesday night for a 13-day visit to the United States, is also
likely to take up the issue with U.S. President Bill Clinton, the
minister added.
</P>
<P>
"Acting U.S. Ambassador A.A. Thibault met me today to share his
country's concern over the international oil prices ... he will
communicate mutual concerns to U.S. President," Naik noted.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the impact of high oil prices would be
significant for India, a major oil importer, but any decision to
raise domestic prices would be taken only after the OPEC meeting
in Vienna this weekend and the return of Vajpayee and Finance
Minister Yashwant Sinha from the United States.
</P>
<P>
According to the PTI, Naik reminded the OPEC in his
communication that it had decided in its June meeting to maintain
the prices in the band of 22 to 28 dollars a barrel, which would
average 26 dollars.
</P>
<P>
India was expressing the feelings of the entire developing
countries, he added. 
</P>
