<HEADLINE> Mbeki's Residence Stolen for Second Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A man in his early 30s
broke into South African President Thabo Mbeki's official
residence in Cape Town sometime between September 1 and 4, the
South African Press Association reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki was in New York at the time of the incident.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, presidential spokeswoman Tasneem Carrim
confirmed that the man had not gained access to the president's
private quarters, but had consumed some of his food and drink.
</P>
<P>
There was also no serious damage to property, she said.
</P>
<P>
According to Carrim, "the man has been arrested and is
presently in police custody awaiting further investigation and
action."
</P>
<P>
However, the statement was silent on how the man managed to
breach security, including police guards in the presidential
compound, especially in the light of the urban terror experienced
in Cape Town over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
It was also not clear how long he had made himself at home
before detection.
</P>
<P>
It is not the first time Mbeki has been victim of theft in Cape
Town, the report said, disclosing that in 1998, when Mbeki was
deputy president, a gardener at the same compound was caught
stealing some Zimbabwean copper chains from him. 
</P>
