<HEADLINE> Second Canadian Athlete Suspended in Doping Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian Olympic team
blocked a second athlete from the up-coming Sydney Games Wednesday
night in another doping scandal.
</P>
<P>
Equestrian Eric Lamaze, a 32-year-old Toronto-area rider, was
suspended after random testing revealed evidence of cocaine use.
</P>
<P>
"It's pretty devastating to the team," said equestrian team
chef d'equipe Terrance Millar.
</P>
<P>
"We are all friends of Eric's and we feel a great sense of
sadness and 'what a waste.' He's a great talent and at the top of
his career," he said.
</P>
<P>
Test results from a second sample are expected from the
Canadian Centre for Ethics in Sport Thursday morning for a final
decision on whether or not Lamaze will compete in Sydney. He has
10 days to appeal the ruling.
</P>
<P>
Lamaze tested positive for cocaine in 1996 and was handed a
four-year suspension, which was later shortened on appeal to seven
months. The rider has ever since insisted he has overcome his past
drug use.
</P>
<P>
Just a few days ago, Edmonton hammer thrower Robin Lyons tested
positive for an anabolic steroid.
</P>
<P>
The 23-year-old hammer thrower, who has launched an appeal of
the finding, said Wednesday that she had never touched a
performance-enhancing drug. She believes several legal dietary
supplements she has taken may have prompted the positive tests for
narandrosterone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
