<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Urges France to End Road Blockades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission on
Thursday called on the French authorities to end road blockades on
grounds that the road obstacles are breaching the EU law of free
movement of people and goods.
</P>
<P>
Jonathan Todd, spokesman for the commission that serves as the
executive body of the 15-nation European Union (EU), said that a
notification had been sent to the French authorities requiring an
answer to the problem within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
French farmers and truck drivers are setting up road blockades
in a protest against the ever-rising prices of fuels in their
country.
</P>
<P>
The French government has already cut down the tax levied on
the fuels. The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC)
has been blamed for its tight production policy that has caused
the recent oil price hike.
</P>
<P>
Todd said the road blockades in France might lead to serious
outcome if the French authorities adopt no effective measures to
end the blockades.
</P>
<P>
It was not the first time that the French had set up road
blockades to protest against national authorities. Other EU member
states, especially those that border with France, are worried by
the act.
</P>
<P>
The rocketing of oil prices posted since early 1999 has
triggered a debate in the EU on the crude oil prices and the three
components of oil price, including refining, distribution and
taxation on oil products.
</P>
<P>
Vice President of the European Commission Loyola de Palacio
said the price hike was mainly due to the production restriction
policy of OPEC.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil prices now seemed determined to fluctuate within a
band of 30 U.S. dollars a barrel and it entered that band in
February following an uninterrupted rise since December 1998 when
the crude oil price bottomed out at 10 dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
Fadhil Chalabi, executive director of the Center for Global
Energy Studies, warned that "if OPEC does not increase its
production, prices will go very high until the peak of the winter.
Prices may even exceed 40 dollars a barrel."
</P>
<P>
OPEC, scheduled to meet over this weekend in Vienna, is
expected to approve an additional production of 500,000 barrels of
crude oil a day. Yet analysts said the production may not suffice
to meet the global demands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Complains About Further Devaluation of Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) on
Thursday complained about the further devaluation of the euro,
which kept hitting record lows in the past two days.
</P>
<P>
"The exchange rate does not reflect the real value of the euro
and contradicts with all the data concerning the EU growth in the
first six months of the year," said Gerassimos Thomas, an official
of the European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
bloc.
</P>
<P>
"The fundamentals of the EU economy are very good," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
When asked what the commission thought of German Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder's comment that had been blamed for the
devaluation of the euro against the U.S. dollar, Thomas said that
the commission would not comment on the remarks by national
politicians.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate and the economic fundamentals would be
discussed by EU finance ministers in their scheduled meeting in
France over the weekend, he added.
</P>
<P>
The EU economy only partly relies on exportation, said Thomas
when asked to comment on the relation between the devaluation and
the increasing EU exports.
</P>
<P>
It was the domestic demand that had greatly boosted the
rekindled economy of the union, he said.
</P>
<P>
The credibility of the euro failed one more test on Wednesday
as traders simply abandoned it, pushing it toward new lows.
</P>
<P>
At one time the euro plunged to 86.85 cents against the dollar
and kept plunging on Thursday in early trading.
</P>
<P>
The single currency went as low as 86.35 cents against the
dollar on Thursday and there seemed to be no immediate brake to
stop the free-falling.
</P>
<P>
Critics said that the panic selling was fanned by the comments
from Schroeder. The German Chancellor said earlier this week that
he was not concerned about the euro's devaluation, that only helps
to make German exports cheaper overseas.
</P>
<P>
Fears that European policy-makers were at odds with the
European Central Bank spread from one exchange market to another
in that the European Central Bank had just raised its benchmark
lending interest rate by a quarter point.
</P>
<P>
Raising interest rates is usually a move that tends to bolster
local currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Calls for Clear Labeling of Eggs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) on
Thursday called for compulsory and clear labeling of eggs about
the way they are produced so as to facilitate consumer choice.
</P>
<P>
"Consumers increasingly care about the way eggs are produced,"
said EU Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler.
</P>
<P>
The compulsory labeling scheme will replace the existing
voluntary labeling scheme.
</P>
<P>
The method by which hens are farmed has become a major factor
in how consumers choose which eggs to buy, said Fischler, adding
that the new labeling scheme will give consumers more right to
choose.
</P>
<P>
Under the new scheme, on eggs or packages will be clear
indication on how the hens are farmed and farming indicator will
appear in phrases such as "free range," "semi-intensive," "deep
litter," and "cage production."
</P>
<P>
Additional information is also encouraged to include the trader,
durability, storage method, origin, selling price, quality and
weight grading.
</P>
<P>
The compulsory labeling will also be applied to egg producers
from non-EU member countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
