<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Acting FM Urges Barak, Arafat to Make Decisions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Israel's acting Foreign
Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami Thursday urged Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to make final decisions on an
Israeli-Palestinian peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on Israel Radio after reports from New York earlier
Thursday showed that U.S. President Bill Clinton failed to break
the deadlock in the peace process, Ben-Ami said "This is no longer
time for negotiations, it's a time for decisions by leaders."
</P>
<P>
Barak and Arafat are both in New York to attend the United
Nations Millennium Summit. They met Clinton separately, the first
meetings since their summit at Camp David last July ended without
an agreement.
</P>
<P>
The bottleneck issue is the fate of Jerusalem, which Israel
claims as its "eternal and undivided capital," while the
Palestinians want Arab East Jerusalem as the capital of their
future state. Israel occupied the eastern part in the 1967 Mideast
War.
</P>
<P>
During and after the Camp David summit, various solutions on the
issue had been raised by U.S., Egyptian and European leaders. But
reports said Arafat did not change his position on the issue while
meeting with Clinton late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart announced that Clinton had
failed in his attempt to bring about a breakthrough in the stalled
Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
He also reported no intention of holding another Camp David
three-way summit, which was widely expected as the last chance to
revive the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami stressed Thursday that Israel had "reached its red
lines" during the Camp David summit, and the negotiations will not
be endless.
</P>
<P>
"We are not hostages and cannot allow ourselves to be hostages.
The government is working in different directions at the same time.
We have a deadline for negotiations," he said, referring to Barak's
plan to set up a broad-based coalition with the major opposition
Likud party in case that a deal with the Palestinians could not be
reached.
</P>
<P>
Such a coalition, which will help Barak restore his
parliamentary majority ahead of the parliament's re-convening at
the end of October, will surely harm the peace process, as Likud
had expressed its objection to making further compromises to the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Attorney Gilad Sher, who is one of Israeli major negotiators
along with Ben-Ami in the past few months, also told Israel Radio
Thursday that in his opinion, Israel had reached the limit of its
flexibility on the issue of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
He added that Arafat should understand that there are only a few
weeks left for the talks, and at the end of that the windows of
opportunities will be shut.
</P>
<P>
He urged Arafat to show more flexibility and openness so as not
to miss the historic chance to end the century-long conflicts
between Jews and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
An official in Barak's delegation to New York had confirmed
Thursday to Israel Radio that the prime minister had set October 6
as the deadline for the Israeli-Palestinian talks. Barak said that
if there is still no progress in the talks, the peace process will
be derailed for a long time.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Congress is due to dissolve on that date and the Americans
will be busy with new presidential elections, scheduled for
November. Israel's Yom Kippur, the most solemn day of the Jewish
calendar, also falls on that day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition Leader Granted Bail in Corruption Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A metropolitan session court
Thursday granted bail to the opposition leader Begum Khaleda Zia
in a corruption case when she appeared in the court Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) leader and former Finance
Minister Saifur Rahman and former Civil Aviation and Tourism
minister Abdul Mannan accused in the case were also granted bail.
</P>
<P>
Khaleda Zia and nine others were prosecuted by the Bureau of
Anti-Corruption for alleged misappropriation of 1.75 billion taka
(34.8 million U.S. dollars) in purchasing two Airbuses from France
in 1994 during the BNP rule. The case was filed on August 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The BNP chief has also been accused in another corruption case
involving nearly 120,000 dollars for decorating her Dhaka Garrison
residence while she was in power from 1991 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
Moving the bail petition, Barrister Maudud Ahmed said the case
against the opposition leader was baseless and preposterous. It
was motivated and intended politically to harass Begum Zia and
other leaders of BNP and tarnish their image and reputation.
</P>
<P>
He argued that people were aware that the case was fictitious
and this kind of false case would not cause any damage to the
United Movement of the opposition. Rather it would strengthen the
stand of the opposition that the government does not believe in
rule of law, he added.
</P>
<P>
Opposing the bail, Public Prosecutor Kamrul Islam submitted
that the accused influential persons, if enlarged on bail, could
mislead the witnesses.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, hearing of a petition filed under section 205
seeking exemption of Begum Zia from personal appearance in the
court was also held Thursday but the court gave no order. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
