<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkmenistan Becomes ADB's 59th Member </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
said Thursday that Turkmenistan, a central Asian country, has
become its 59th member, a decision effective on August 31 this
year.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-based multilateral financial body said in a news
release issued here that it will soon send an economic mission to
Turkmenistan to help decide how it can best assist its newest
member.
</P>
<P>
ADB, which seeks to reduce poverty in Asia, expects to focus on
giving the poor better access to income-generating opportunities
and to basic social services in the country. ADB will also support
the government in reforming the economy.
</P>
<P>
The ADB said state-owned enterprises in Turkmenistan still
comprise 90 percent of the country's economy, which is undergoing
transition from a command to a market economy.
</P>
<P>
According to the ADB, the country's economy is mainly dependent
on the production of primary goods, especially natural gas, oil
and cotton.
</P>
<P>
However, it added, Turkmenistan is heavily dependent on food
imports. Textiles and hydrocarbon processing dominate the
industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan became independent from the former Soviet Union in
October 1991 and is the fourth largest territory among the former
Soviet states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stage Set for American Hostage's Release Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A Philippine government
negotiator said Thursday that the stage has been set for the
holding of formal negotiations for the freedom of the 24-year-old
American Jeffrey Schilling who has been kidnapped by the Abu
Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
Sulu Vice-Governor Munib Estino, the appointed Philippine
government negotiator, told local reporters in Jolo, capital of
the southern Philippine island province of Sulu, that he has sent
an emissary to the Abu Sayyaf's lair in Paikul town Thursday
morning with pen, paper and a video camera to record the formal
demands of the terrorists in exchange for the safe release of
Schilling.
</P>
<P>
Estino said that as soon as the emissary returns to Jolo, he
will immediately transmit the demands or any statements from the
kidnappers or from Schilling to the government for their proper
action.
</P>
<P>
Estino said he was informed that Schilling is in good physical
condition but that the American is given to tantrums, especially
when he is moved from one place to another.
</P>
<P>
The negotiator also appealed to all agencies or persons who
bring any medicines, foodstuff, or other goods to Schilling or who
contact the Abu Sayyaf holding him to coordinate with him to
prevent any complications that could prejudice his effort to
obtain Schilling's early and safe release.
</P>
<P>
Estino categorically refuted the Abu Sayyaf's claim that
Schilling is a member of the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency (CIA)
or that he is a gunrunner.
</P>
<P>
He also confirmed previous reports that Schilling was indeed
invited by the Abu Sayyaf to visit them in Jolo so he could meet
some of the relatives of his wife, Ivy Osani. Osani is said to be
a relative of a Abu Sayyaf's leader.
</P>
<P>
Estino said Schilling went to Jolo voluntarily on August 28 but
has been forcibly detained by the terrorists since then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
