<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 11 Nigerian Products to Enjoy U.S. Duty-Free Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- About 11 products from Nigeria
will qualify for duty-free status into the United States under the
Generalized System of Preferences (GSP) recently announced by
President Bill Clinton during his visit to the west African
country, The Punch newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a statement from the U.S. Embassy in the
capital Abuja as saying that these include electrical, electronic,
leather, plastic, rubber and metal and textile products.
</P>
<P>
According to the duty-free program, Nigeria would be allowed to
diversify its oil-dominated export base, such as sports equipment
and materials, biscuits and confectioneries, paper materials and
pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day state visit to Nigeria in late August,
Clinton announced that the west African country would be included
among the beneficiaries of the GSP in a bid to deepen the economic
partnership between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that more than 4,650 products from about 140
countries worldwide enjoy American GSP status, which provides non-
reciprocal tariff preferences for products from the developing
countries into the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
The United States, which imported Nigeria's agricultural and
textile products worth 14 million U.S. dollars in 1998, is the
major export market of the west African country, accounting for 44
percent of its total export. 
</P>
</TEXT>
