<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Government Wants National Vote on Swisscom Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Swiss government is calling
for a nationwide referendum on the privatization of
telecommunications operator Swisscom, and the creation of a post
office bank, the Swiss Radio International reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government hoped that the decision will prevent lengthy
political and legal wrangling.
</P>
<P>
Legal experts argue that it would be unconstitutional for the
government to give up its majority share in Swisscom or introduce
postal banking services without the approval of the Swiss people
and cantons.
</P>
<P>
However, the government said a parliamentary debate on whether
the move was in line with the constitution would only delay
implementation of its plans, which, it said, needed to be
introduced "urgently."
</P>
<P>
It is expected that selling its shares in Swisscom will leave
the company better placed to form business alliances abroad, and
will also provide the money for creating a post office bank.
</P>
<P>
The government decision has preempted moves by trade unions and
one of the country's leading political parties to call for
referendums of their own. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
