<HEADLINE> Court Rejects Li Ping's Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing Higher People's
Court today turned down Li Ping's appeal and maintaining the
Beijing Intermediate People's Court's sentence.
</P>
<P>
Li, the mistress of Cheng Kejie, former vice-chairman of the
National People's Congress Standing Committee and chairman of the
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region who was sentenced to death for
taking huge bribes, is charged of colluding with Cheng in taking
bribes and collaborating with other people in smuggling cases.
</P>
<P>
On August 9, the intermediate court granted Li a life penalty,
plus the confiscation of her personal properties worth 26.88
million HK dollars (one U.S. dollar equals 7.8 HK dollars) and a
fine of 400,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The intermediate court has made the conviction based on
evidence provided by the public persecutor and Li's own confession.
</P>
<P>
In their criminal collaboration, Li took the charge of "looking
for" business opportunities, while the former Guangxi leader was
responsible for settling the deal by using his political power.
Once the deal was made, Li would keep the profits.
</P>
<P>
The intermediate court has thus regarded Li as a main offender.
The court found that both Li and Zhang Jinghai, a Hong Kong
businessman, were playing an equal role in smuggling duty-free
cars.
</P>
<P>
Also today, the higher court rejected an appeal from the Hong
Kong businessman, for collaborating with Li in the smuggling of
other goods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
