<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> West Nile Virus Spreads in Israel, Kills 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSAELM, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Two elderly people infected
with the West Nile virus died Wednesday night in hospital at Kfar
Saba, in the central part of Israel, bringing to six the number of
people who died of the virus in the past year.
</P>
<P>
West Nile virus, transmitted to humans after they are bitten by
an infected mosquito, can in some instances lead to encephalitis, a
dangerous swelling of the brain.
</P>
<P>
Older people and those with weakened immune systems run the
highest risk of developing severe illness from the disease whose
symptoms resemble severe flu, with fever often accompanied by poor
muscle control or mental disorientation.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Health Ministry officials confirmed on Thursday that
four other people have died from the disease this summer. And two
others have been hospitalized after being diagnosed with the virus
and they are in a critical condition.
</P>
<P>
The ministry disclosed that 40 people have been infected with
the virus, which is commonly found in Africa, Eastern Europe, West
Asia, and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Addressing fears of an epidemic, particularly in the central
part of the country, the ministry termed the fatality as a "
seasonal outbreak" of the virus which is endemic in this part of
the world.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays there is a greater awareness of the virus and therefore
it is more clearly diagnosed than in previous years, a ministry
official said.
</P>
<P>
This year's outbreak was first detected two weeks ago when the
virus manifested itself in 23 birds out of 25 in a nature reserve
in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The virus is transmitted through mosquitoes that have bitten
migrating birds infected with the disease.
</P>
<P>
Three months ago the Israeli health, agriculture, and
environment ministries initiated a joint watch program intended to
prevent the spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
The Environment Ministry is now taking steps to spray areas
where there is a danger of mosquitoes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs Oppose Israeli Control of Islamic Sites in Jerusalem: Mubarak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
has reiterated that the Arab people will never accept Israeli
control of Islamic holy sites in Jerusalem and that this unanimity
will not be compromised, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Arabs are opposed to Israeli sovereignty over religious
symbols in Jerusalem, especially Al-Aqsa mosque, Islam's third
holiest site, and this position was not open for negotiation,
Mubarak told Samir Ragab, editor-in-chief of Al-Gomhuria daily, in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
He asserted that the Arab people categorically reject any sort
of concessions on the religious symbols of Islam in Jerusalem, holy
to Muslims, Jews and Christians.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian leader stressed that the issue of Jerusalem is "
very sensitive and must be dealt with carefully to avoid potential
setbacks" in the peace talks between the Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The peace process has been stuck over Jerusalem. Israel occupied
East Jerusalem in the 1967 Mideast War and later declared the whole
city its "eternal and indivisible capital," a claim never
recognized internationally. The Palestinians want the eastern
sector of the city as the capital of their future independent
state.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak called on Israel to seize opportunity and hammer out a
peace agreement with the Palestinians to put an end to the 52-year-
long conflict in the Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
