<HEADLINE> Australia Launches National Threatened Species Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Australia launched a National
Threatened Species Day in Sydney Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Australian Associate Press, at the launching
ceremony the World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) revealed that About
1,400 Australian animal and plant species are at risk of
extinction.
</P>
<P>
"Australia has one of the most diverse ranges of species in the
world, yet many of our unique species are listed as vulnerable and
some 1,400 are currently at risk of extinction," an Australia
spokesman for WWF was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
At the same ceremony, Australian federal Environment Minister
Robert Hill announced a government funding of 490,000 Australian
dollars (276,850 U.S. dollars ) for community grants to help
preserve endangered species in their local environments.
</P>
<P>
Since European occupation 200 years ago, Australia has lost
about 87 plant and 53 animal species, the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
