<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Parliament Regrets Over Atambua Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's House of
Representative expressed here Thursday its regret over the Atambua
incident during which three staff members of the U.N.High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) were killed on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaker of the parliament Akbar Tandjung told reporters that
the Indonesian government and the Indonesian Military (TNI) were
not responsible for the bloody incident.
</P>
<P>
"The government and the military have nothing to do with the
incident. The incident took place, as East Timorese were involved
in their own conflict. That is their own business, not our
government or military's (business). We have nothing to do with
that," Tandjung told reporters at the parliament building.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday afternoon, at least three staff members of the
UNHCR were killed when an angry mob of pro-Jakarta East Timorese
or so-called militia launched an armed attack on the
representative office of the UNHCR in Atambua, a city in Indonesia
's East Nusa Tenggara Province.
</P>
<P>
Separately, in an interview with Xinhua, Chairman Yasril Ananta
Baharuddin of the House Commission I on security and foreign
affairs said his commission regretted the incident and expressed
its condolences to the UNHCR over the loss of its staff members.
</P>
<P>
He further indicated that there might be political conspiracy
behind the incident which in fact coincided with the U.N.Millenium
Summit in New York.
</P>
<P>
"The incident was questionable. Why such an incident took place
and coincided with the U.N. summit? I suggest that there is
political conspiracy made by both nationals and foreigners, which
is aimed at discrediting the administration of President
Abdurrahman Wahid," he said.
</P>
<P>
He further asked the government to launch a comprehensive
investigation into the incident. "We urge the government to launch
an investigation and bring those who were responsible to the court.
"
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Antara reported from New York that Indonesian
President Abdurrahman Wahid has conveyed his deep condolences to
the U.N.secretary-general over the death of three UNHCR staff
members, saying he has instructed Commander of the TNI Adm. Widodo
to carry out a thorough investigation into the incident. 
</P>
