<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Considers Tax Break for Venture Capital Fund Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia said Thursday
that it is considering giving a tax break to companies that start
venture capital (VC) funds.
</P>
<P>
The Treasury is deliberating on the tax break proposal,
Malaysian International Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz
said Thursday,hoping a decision would be made during the tabling
of the country's budget next month.
</P>
<P>
Large corporations especially those in the electronics sector
are the best candidates to formulate the VC funds, which are used
to promote information technology (IT) start-ups, Rafidah said at
the sidelines of the three-day MSC (Multimedia Super Corridor)
International Advisory Panel (IAP) meeting which opened in
Cyberjaya near here earlier Thursday.
</P>
<P>
She said the formulation of VC funds among companies was
emphasized during the open discussions between IAP members and
representatives at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
She said VC funds could be channeled to the small start-ups
involved in multimedia, electronics and other IT-related fields so
that they need not be heavily-dependent on banks for funds but
could look to the VC funds by large corporations which are much
more effective for their type of business.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, IAP member Gilbert Amelio, who is the chief
executive officer of Beneventure Capital, told reporters also at
the sidelines of the meeting that Malaysia's infant VC industry
and technopreneurship would get a jump-start if its VC companies
could form partnerships with VCs from other countries.
</P>
<P>
The partnerships would enable the creation of infrastructure,
knowledge and momentum to develop the VC industry, Amelio said.
</P>
<P>
The MSC launched in 1996 is a 50 square kilometers by 15 square
kilometers zone, stretching from Kuala Lumpur southwards,
designated as a hub for the development of multimedia products and
services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
