<HEADLINE> No Hurdle on Pak Side to Iran-India Gas Pipeline: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Petroleum
Minister Unsman Aminuddin said here Thursday that there is no
hurdle from Pakistan's side to the construction of the gas
pipeline between Iran and India.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Middle East Broadcasting Corporation,
he said Pakistan had responded positively to the request of the
Iranian government for the gas pipeline and shown its willingness
to remove the security concerns expressed by the Indian government.
</P>
<P>
The 2,670-kilometer pipeline from Iran to India via Pakistan is
expected to bring around 700 million U.S dollars in revenue per
annum to Pakistan. Meanwhile, as the only way for India to get gas
facility from Iran, Pakistan will reap a transit fee from the
pipeline project worth 500 million dollars annually while another
amount of 200 million dollars will be saved per annum by getting
cheaper gas from the project. 
</P>
