<HEADLINE> Forest Fire Threatens Queensland State of Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Forest fire is threatening
Queensland state of Australia because of lack of rain.
</P>
<P>
According to the Australian Associated Press, the state's
Emergency Services Minister Stephen Robertson warned Thursday that
almost all of Queensland was tinder dry and ready to explode into
damaging bushfires.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Queensland Fire and Rescue Authority's
emergency bushfire headquarters, the state minister said, "The
fire situation is very serious and 95 percent of the state is a
ticking firebomb ready to explode."
</P>
<P>
During the past three weeks, the state's southeast corner
reportedly saw thousands of fires, which were described as the
worst since 1994.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, at least 80 to 90 percent of the
fires have been deliberately lit.
</P>
<P>
No casualties were reported so far.
</P>
<P>
A total of 50,000 permanent and volunteer firefighters were on
full alert while parents were asked to ensure that their children
were not deliberately lighting fires.
</P>
<P>
Anyone convicted of deliberately lighting a bushfire faces up
to seven years in jail or a fine of 35,000 Australian dollars (19,
775 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
