<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Satisfied With Tanzania's Good Implementation of Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has
praised Tanzania for its impressive performance in the bank
supported projects during the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Some 95 percent of the country's portfolio of projects financed
by the World Bank was rated satisfactory, up from 76 percent in
fiscal year 1997, according to a statement jointly issued here
Thursday by the bank and the Tanzanian Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
Projects at risk in the portfolio declined from 52 percent in
1997 to 5 percent in fiscal year 2000, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The good news is that Tanzania has achieved impressive
performance in its portfolio during the past two years, not only
within the Africa region but also relative to the performance of
countries elsewhere," the World Bank Country Director for Tanzania
and Uganda Jim Adams said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
The impressive improvement of the Tanzanian portfolio may be
ascribed, among other reasons, to a number of good practices in
portfolio management adopted by both the government and the bank
in the past two years, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
The practices include closer collaboration between Tanzania
Country Office of the World Bank and the government's counterpart
officials in resolving policy and implementation issues.
</P>
<P>
However, the statement also warned that there are many new
challenges that need to be addressed over the next two years if
Tanzania continues to maintain its strong performance.
</P>
<P>
These include preparing Annual Work Plans in time, addressing
the shortage of counterpart funds from the Tanzanian government
and learning incorporation lessons from the past implementation
experience to the current portfolio.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian government and the World Bank ended a two-day
meeting on Wednesday for a detailed review of the performance of
Tanzania's portfolio projects.
</P>
<P>
The biennial meeting is part of the World Bank's institutional
system of monitoring and assessing outcomes and impacts of its
various interventions.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has sought to actively support Tanzania's
economic recovery efforts as evidenced by some 131 Bank financed
projects, among which 110 have been completed since 1960s.
</P>
<P>
The portfolio comprises 23 projects with total commitments of
about 1.3 billion U.S. dollars. The bank is presently working on
four to five projects a year across most major sectors, but with a
growing emphasis on social sector programs which cover health,
education and capacity building. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
