<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak took the world's stage on
Wednesday at the U.N. Millennium Summit and, after pledging that "
Jerusalem will remain united and open to all who love her," also
admitted the importance of the city to the Palestinian neighbors.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman in the Prime Minister's Office said this marked the
first time that an Israeli leader acknowledged a Palestinian
connection to Jerusalem in such terms.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat met U.
S. President Bill Clinton late Wednesday night and was to give an
updated reply to the American peace proposals that he rejected at
Camp David in July.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Clinton met Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who has
taken advantage of his presence at the U.N. Millennium Summit in
New York to try organizing an international campaign to pressure
Arafat to be flexible and not unilaterally declare a Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
Clinton plans to use the next two days to hold intensive talks
with Barak and Arafat to try to score a breakthrough and get a
permanent settlement.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- The Israeli Defense Forces (IDF) will publish on Thursday the
conclusions of its inquiry into the operational blunders of the
Duvdevan reconnaissance unit that left three soldiers killed by
friendly fire while tracking a member of the Islamic militant Hamas
group on August 26.
</P>
<P>
Chief of General Staff Shaul Mofaz is expected to accept the
resignation of the commander of the IDF in the West Bank Brigadier
General Shlomo Oren.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel's ultra-Orthodox Shas party Chairman Eli Yishai said
on Wednesday that he would go directly to Public Security Minister
Shlomo Ben-Ami to complain about the conditions, in which former
party leader Aryeh Deri is imprisoned at Ma'asiyahu Prison in
Ramle, near Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
The former party leader and cabinet minister, convicted of
bribe-taking and other charges, began serving a three-year prison
term on Sunday. 
</P>
