<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Refutes U.S. Accusation Concerning Religious Freedom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam Thursday criticized the
United States for interfering in the internal affairs of other
countries, saying the United States has no right to judge the
religious situation in other nations.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese law stipulates and the state of Vietnam guarantees
that all the country's citizens enjoy the right to freely practice
a religion or not to practice a religion, spokesman of the
Vietnamese Foreign Ministry Le Dung said at a press conference
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were in response to a question on Vietnam's
reaction to a report on religious freedom issued by the U.S. State
Department on September 5. The report warned against religious
repression in a number of countries in the Middle East and Asia,
including Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Dung said the right is contained in the Vietnamese Constitution
and respected in reality.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman affirmed that there is no such thing as the state
of Vietnam represses or hinders religious activities.
</P>
<P>
In a country with many religions and beliefs, Vietnamese
citizens, whether adhering to a religion or not adhering to a
religion, have equal rights before the law.
</P>
<P>
He said that in Vietnam, religious activities which serve
legitimate and lawful interests of religious adherents are secured.
Religious activities which serve the fatherland and people's
interests are encouraged.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman accused the United States of delegating itself a
right to judge the religious situation in other countries, saying
this is contrary to the fundamental principles of international
law and represents an interference in the internal affairs of
other countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
