<HEADLINE> China's Bond Market Slumps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- China's T-bond market slumped
as the stock market rebounded from a week-long decline today.
</P>
<P>
Out flow of capital from the treasury bond market to the stock
market caused the prices of fixed income treasuries to drop 0.15
percent on average, according to Homeway, China's leading on-line
financial and securities advisory company.
</P>
<P>
All bonds saw a decline of prices today, pushing yield to the
highest level since mid-August.
</P>
<P>
Transaction value totaled 1.63 billion yuan, 454 million yuan
more than on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
China's repurchasing market turned bullish with expanded
turnover and higher prices. Trade volume of 3-day, 7-day, 14-day
and 28-day repurchasing soared by 6.74 billion yuan to 8.11
billion yuan. The interest rate of the 3-day repurchasing
agreement jumped to 4.90 percent from 3.21 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
