<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Foundation Donates to Forestation Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Lee Foundation Singapore today
donated one million Hong Kong dollars to China's forestation drive
in desertification-ridden areas.
</P>
<P>
Xu Yongguang, deputy director-general of China Youth
Development Foundation (CYDF), which is responsible for the drive,
said that this was the largest overseas donation ever received by
the foundation.
</P>
<P>
The man-made woodland, which is to cover 330 hectares, will be
situated in Huailai County, north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
Forestation experts say the project will not only improve local
ecological conditions, but also help curb desert from invading
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Desertification in Huailai, adjacent to suburbs of Beijing,
creates many difficulties for the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
At the donation ceremony, Niu Maosheng, governor of Hebei, said
that his province will pour additional funds of nine million yuan
(1.1 million U.S. dollars) into the project.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Qiang, chairman of the CYDF, said that his foundation will
strictly supervise the project implementation and expenditure.
</P>
<P>
Together with a group of governmental bodies, the CYDF kicked
off the forestation drive in January 1999, enhancing the whole
society's consciousness of preventing pollution and safeguarding
environment in the country.
</P>
<P>
CYDF has received donations totaling 40 million yuan, funding
forestation in eight provinces, two autonomous regions and one
municipality alongside the Yellow River and the Yangtze River.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
