<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Opens Anti-Drugs Exhibition Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has opened an anti-
drugs exhibition center here to enhance public awareness about the
dangers of illicit drugs, according to a report from the Thai
government Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The center, inaugurated by Jurin Laksanavisit, minister of the
prime minister's office Wednesday, uses wax model, samples,
pictures and graphics to show the inside story of drug production
and transportation, the damage of drugs to the people and society
and the measures to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
The most striking exhibit is a wax model showing a desperate
methamphetamine addict holding a child at knife point based on a
real criminal case in the capital city in which a drug addict
seized and murdered a toddler.
</P>
<P>
The center, which cost the Thai government 5 million baht (122,
000 U.S. dollars) to build, is part of the government's efforts to
deal with the worsening drug problem, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Thai authorities estimated that at least 600 million
amphetamine pills have been smuggled into the country since last
year. Meanwhile, more than 600,000 Thai teenagers are using
illegal drugs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
