<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Leader Thanks Estrada for Safe Hostages Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
thanked Philippine President Joseph Estrada for the safe release
of the French hostages who were among the foreigners held captive
in the southern Philippines by the Abu Sayyaf, an official said
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Presidential Spokesman Ricardo Puno said in a press
briefing here that President Chirac, who met President Estrada in
New York before the opening of the U.N. Millennium Summit, also
expressed the hope that the Philippine government will succeed in
seeking the safe release of the remaining hostages.
</P>
<P>
Puno said that during the brief meeting between the two leaders,
the French president conveyed the gratitude of his country to the
Philippines in getting French woman Sonia Wendling and French
television reporter Maryse Burgot safely home.
</P>
<P>
Wendling and Burgot were among the foreigners set free by the
Abu Sayyaf after months of negotiations that involved Philippine
local and national officials, with the support of former Libyan
Ambassador Rajab Azzarou.
</P>
<P>
Puno said the remaining three French hostages -- Loisy Stephane
and TV crew members Jean Jacques Le Garrec and Roland Madura --
are set to be released Friday along with Seppo Franti and Risto
Vahannen from Finland and Marc Waller and Filipino Roland Ulla
from Germany. 
</P>
