<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Truckers Continue Blocking Oil Refineries in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- French truckers continued to
block oil refineries and storehouses and began blocking some
highways on Thursday, while taxi drivers were joining the protest
against the rise of fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
A total of 102 oil storehouses or refineries were blocked
Thursday morning while about 50 road blocks were set up on the
highways by truckers to stop traffic flows, said the National
Center of Road Information.
</P>
<P>
The traffic on the highways leading to the central city of Lyon
and the southwest city of Bordeaux were seriously disrupted by the
blockade.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, taxi drivers tried to block the traffic to the
Mediterranean city of Montpellier by setting up blockades at four
axis which lead to the center of the city, according to Agence
France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
Two of the three national unions of truckers rejected on
Wednesday an offer by the government to cut fuel tax by 35
centimes (about five U.S. cents) per liter this year and 25
centimes (about 3.5 cents) next year.
</P>
<P>
Transport Minister Jean-Claude Gayssot said on Thursday that
the government has done its maximum to end the crisis and it is
impossible for it to make more concessions.
</P>
<P>
The unrest which began on Monday has resulted in a serious
shortage of oil supply in France. And in more than half of the
country, oil sale at service stations is being rationed and many
stations are closed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
