<HEADLINE> Malaysia Satisfied With Indonesia's Probe Into Attacks on Missions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Inspector-
General of Police Norian Mai said Thursday that he is satisfied
with the investigation so far by the Indonesian police into the
recent incidents at two Malaysian missions in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian police chief went to Jakarta on Monday and met
his Indonesian counterpart, Rusdi Hardjo, to get full information
on the two incidents.
</P>
<P>
"I want to say that I'm satisfied with the investigation by the
Indonesian police on the two incidents," he told reporters after
attending a function in Petaling Jaya near here.
</P>
<P>
The investigation is continuing and the motive has yet to be
ascertained, Norian said, adding that he was informed that the
Indonesian police had detained six people to help in the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
He said he had also received assurance from the Indonesian
police to step up security at Malaysian missions in that country.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian Embassy in Jakarta was hit on August 27 by a hand
grenade hurled by unidentified individuals, which exploded in its
compound. Four days later, the Malaysian Consulate in Pontianak,
West Kalimantan, was attacked by a mob with stones and other
objects. 
</P>
