<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Import Sugar to Relieve Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Sugar Authority has
been allowed to import 10,000 tons of sugar every month to address
the current shortage, media here reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But, the authority will pay taxes and duty at 125 percent for
importing white mill sugar and the levies will be strictly
enforced to protect cane growers, Kenyan Agriculture Minister
Chris Obure said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Obure said the country was steeped in a sugar crisis and
available supply had gone down from 40,000 to 30,000 tons monthly.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will also review sugar sales to bulk
buyers to reduce chances of creating artificial shortage, adding "
there must be other underlying factors aggravating the situation
such as deliberate hoarding by unscrupulous traders with a view of
enriching themselves."
</P>
<P>
Apart from "selfish" traders hoarding sugar to make higher
profits, the minister also blamed the current drought for poor
sugarcane production.
</P>
<P>
He called for accelerating the sugarcane land development and
replantation, and taking strict surveillance at borders to prevent
sugar smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Since last month, Kenya has experienced a sugar shortage
nationwide and the price of sugar has gone up by some 30 percent
at supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
Sugar production between January and June this year reportedly
stood at 255,608 tons, compared with 218,779 tons during the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
However, Obure said, annual domestic demand has steadily risen
to 609,428 tons compared with an output of 470,788 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Concern Voiced Over Fires in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya National Chamber of
Commerce and Industry has expressed concern at the increased
incidents of fires with heavy economic losses.
</P>
<P>
A seven-hour inferno gutted Nairobi's largest open-air market
on early Wednesday. Last week, a fire destroyed another major open-
fire market in the downtown of Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Kassim Owango, chairman of the chamber, urged the government on
Wednesday to investigate the causes of the two fires in which
traders have lost property worth billions of shillings (one U.S.
dollar is equal to 76 shillings).
</P>
<P>
The fires that razed the Freemarket last week and the Gikomba
market on Wednesday seemed to be an organized vendetta against
small-scale traders, Owango claimed.
</P>
<P>
"Unless the perpetrators are sought, arrested and charged, many
more people are going to suffer economic loss and become jobless,"
the East African Standard quoted Owango on Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The burning of the two markets will cause a major security risk
in the city, as most of the traders whose stalls were burned will
have no choice but to move to the expensive shop-dominated Central
Business District in Nairobi, Owango said.
</P>
<P>
He said fires were adding extra pain to Kenyans who are
suffering from the severe economic recession. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
