<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Likely to Give More Fund to Kenya in Combating Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Daily Nation newspaper Thursday quoted Kenyan Finance
Permanent Secretary Martin Oduor-Otieno as saying the government
and the IMF/World Bank team which had been negotiating for nine
days here, agreed that the drought would "materially alter the
original budget."
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government made the request to the IMF team to
review the impact of drought on the country and to modify program
agreed to under the poverty reduction and growth facility.
</P>
<P>
"The drought will lead to a reduction in government revenue
and the overall economic growth prospects from those originally
set out," Oduor said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
A joint IMF/World Bank team visited Kenya beginning from August
25 and held successful discussions with the government officials
and other development partners on the impact of drought on various
sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Oduor said the Kenyan government expected to incur more drought-
related expenditure in food relief, emergency water needs in the
capital Nairobi and other areas, power generation, agriculture,
health and education.
</P>
<P>
"We will now make presentations on the financing strategy and
resource gap in October to the IMF board for consideration," Oduor
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
