<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Than 1,000 Correspondents to Cover Upcoming China Investment, Trade Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A total of 1,200 Chinese and
foreign journalists have gathered in this east China city to cover
the forthcoming China Investment and Trade Fair scheduled for
September 8-12.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the event's organizing committee said that the
number of reporters rose by 70 percent over last year. The
correspondents come from China's mainland, Hong Kong, Macao and
Taiwan, southeast Asian countries, European countries, the United
States and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that a special website on the trade fair has
been launched on the Internet and the opening ceremony of the
event will be broadcast live worldwide through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
At present, the China Investment and Trade Fair is the only
national economic and trading activity in China which focuses on
luring foreign funds.
</P>
<P>
Economist Yan Zheng attributed the increase in the number of
correspondents to the fact that the Chinese economy has made a
turn for the better. He also said China's soon-to-be-realized
accession into the World Trade Organization (WTO) and the economic
situation in Asian countries, which have shed off the effect of
the Asian financial crisis, also shows a trend of going up.
</P>
<P>
Senior Chinese officials have expressed at the beginning of the
year that it is not a long way to go before China's accession into
the WTO. This means that China will open up more fields to foreign
investors. Moreover, the fact that the economies of southeast
Asian countries have begun to recover from the financial crisis
also means that more funds will flow into China.
</P>
<P>
China will issue a series of opening policies which include
encouraging foreign investors to pour money into high-tech
industries and central and western regions of China at the
upcoming trade fair, according to reliable sources.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that China approved 11,891 foreign-
funded enterprises in the January-July period this year, an
increase of 26.93 percent over the same period last year.
Contracted foreign investment was 27.64 billion U.S. dollars,
rising 24.04 percent.
</P>
<P>
As of July this year, China has approved more than 353,700
overseas-funded enterprises, involving a combined contractual
foreign investment of 641.7 billion U.S. dollars. The used foreign
investment amounted to 327.7 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
