<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Better Way to Convert Natural Gas Into Petrochemical Materials in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- China has developed a more
efficient way to convert natural gas into petrochemical materials
using microwave catalyzing technology, opening up a new way to
better use natural gas resources.
</P>
<P>
The technology will increase the one-way C2 hydrocarbon yield
rate to 70 percent from 6 percent in using the traditional method,
while the highest yield rate in developed countries is 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
And by using the direct plasma conversion method under normal
or high air pressure, the one-way ethene yield rate has increased
25 percent, which was claimed the highest in the world by its
developers.
</P>
<P>
The technology was developed by a group of researchers headed
by Dr. Zhang Jinsong, a research fellow at the Metal Research
Institute of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS), as one of the
key State-funded research programs between 1996-2000.
</P>
<P>
It is very complicated and expensive to convert natural gas
into commonly used petrochemical materials like ethene and ethyne
and scientists around the world are trying to find more efficient
ways to produce ethene and ethyne, said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The new technique and related experimental facilities have
passed an appraisal by experts last month, which was organized by
the Ministry of Sciences and Technology.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said the prospects are bright for the application of the
new technique, as the country's verified natural gas reserve has
been growing and more natural gas will be used by petrochemical
plants in China, particularly in the country's western region,
which has an abundance of natural gas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Auto Tail Gas Purifier Developed in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- China has developed the world'
s first auto exhaust gas purifier using microwave catalyzing
technology, which is capable of rendering the purified exhaust gas
up to European standard EU2.
</P>
<P>
The purified exhaust gas is also very close to EU3, or the
next generation auto exhaust emission standard set by the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
The purifier was developed by a group of researchers headed by
Dr. Zhang Jinsong, a research fellow at the Institute of Metal
Research, under the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS), as one of
the key State-funded research programs between 1996-2000.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said they also developed another exhaust gas purifying
technique using an improved electric catalysis with similar
results.
</P>
<P>
He said the two techniques, already patented, could meet EU2
standards, which will be introduced in 2004 by China as its
standard for auto exhaust gas emission for the next generation.
</P>
<P>
"Commercializing the two techniques in China and application
by Chinese auto plants of the techniques will break the monopoly
of overseas products and techniques on the Chinese auto exhaust
gas purifier markets," said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The auto exhaust gas purifier market in China has been
dominated by American and German products, as locally made
purifiers could not meet the requirements of the EU1, or the No.1
auto exhaust gas emission standard set by the European Union,
currently used by China as the national standard.
</P>
<P>
The new technique and its products have passed an appraisal by
experts last month, which was organized by the Ministry of
Sciences and Technology.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said the techniques will be used by the Changchun-based
China First Automobile Group Corp., one of the three leading auto
plants in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
