<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Boost Garment, Textile Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam plans to boost its
garment and textile production and export by investing 11 trillion
Vietnamese dong (785 million U.S. dollars) in new technology and
build 10 new textile plants between 2001 and 2005, local daily
Vietnam News(VNS) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The move is aimed at making preparations for the country's
freeing up of trade on the international market.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam hopes to double its garment and textile export turnover
within five years and triple it within 10 years, VNS quoted an
official of Vietnam National Textile and Garment Corporation as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"Based on the 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of exports expected
this year," the official said, "Vietnam's turnover should increase
to 4 billion U.S. dollars in 2005 and 7 billion U.S. dollars in
2010."
</P>
<P>
The garment and textile sector of the country also plans to
increase the country's exports to the United State from just 4
percent of the sector's total export turnover currently, to 44
percent by 2010, equal to the current exports to the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
The official also added that as many as 188 projects in textile
and garment factories worth 179 million dollars were carried out
to improve product quality and design and diversify products to
meet market demands.
</P>
<P>
Under the industry's 10-year growth plan, 1 billion meters of
cloth is expected to be produced, of which 600 million meters will
be suitable for making export garments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
