<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, IMF Sign new Letter of Intent on Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government and
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) signed here Thursday a new
agreement on Indonesia's economic reform program, which will pave
the way for a fresh IMF loan disbursement to the country.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, also called the letter of intent, was signed
simultaneously by Indonesia's Coordinating Minister for Economic
Affairs Rizal Ramli here and First Deputy Managing Director of IMF
Stanley Fischer in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The new accord, which was revised from the previous one, is
largely the same as the previous pact, but it is more
comprehensive compared with the agreement signed on July 31, 2000,
as it contains a 10-point economic recovery program recommended by
the new economic team of the Indonesian government.
</P>
<P>
The 10-point program includes intensifying the government's
commitment to the development of small and medium industries, to
corporate and banking restructuring, to the privatization program,
to the increase of domestic and foreign investment and to the
development of infrastructure projects in villages.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has seriously carried out the reform
agenda stipulated in the agreement signed on July 31 by the two
sides, including macroeconomic policy, fiscal decentralization,
banking system reforms, corporate restructuring, legal reform and
governance, public sector reform and governance.
</P>
<P>
To speed up the economic recovery, the IMF will focus its
efforts on macroeconomic stability and fiscal balance. And the
World Bank and the Asian Development Bank will play a greater role
in agriculture,privatization, small and medium industries and
infrastructure projects in villages.
</P>
<P>
Senior Representative of IMF in Jakarta John Dodsworth Told
Xinhua after the signing of the letter of intent that the IMF will
disburse the next package of loan in third week of September.
</P>
<P>
"But I can't not say the exact number (of the loan package that
will be disbursed). But generally that is around 400 million U.S.
dollars," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The letter of intent has to be approved by the IMF Board of
Directors before the loan can be disbursed.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement, the IMF should disburse 400 million
of its 5 billion U.S. dollars bailout fund to Indonesia at the end
of August. The IMF has so far disbursed more than 700 million
dollars since it made the pledge in January this year to help the
country finance its three-year economic program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
