<HEADLINE> Zambian Police Arrest 8 Gunmen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambian police in Lusaka have
arrested eight of nine suspected gunmen from a government house
whose backyard had been turned into a make-shift garage, Times of
Zambia newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
During their operation, the police recovered 10 guns, more than
100 rounds of live ammunition and five stolen motor vehicles from
the suspected robbers. While in the garage, stolen vehicles were
dismantled and reassembled before they were sold.
</P>
<P>
This was confirmed by Lusaka division police chief of
operations Peter Chingaipe and Emmasdale police officer-in-charge
Florence Bobo on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Chingaipe as saying the first suspect was
apprehended at a servant's quarters he was renting after he stole
a Toyota Corolla which police recovered.
</P>
<P>
Police later searched the house and recovered the 10 firearms,
99 rounds of live ammunition for the AK rifles and 21 rounds of
9mm pistol live bullets which were also hidden there, Chingaipe
said.
</P>
<P>
Police were still interrogating one of the suspects whom they
believed was part of a notorious gang of dangerous criminals that
had been terrorizing residents in the city, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bobo said four stolen motor vehicles were recovered
from another house in the city, adding that one of the former
government officer's son was being held together with seven other
suspectes. Two more people were being sought in connection with
the discoveries which also included forged plates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
