<HEADLINE> U.S. Air Force Plane Crashes, Killing Pilot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. Air Force training
plane crashed Wednesday during a student training flight, killing
the pilot, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The T-37 aircraft went down in clear weather in a plowed field
about two km north of Vance Air Force Base, which is located on
the outskirts of Enid, about 130 km north-northwest of Oklahoma
City.
</P>
<P>
The name of the pilot killed was being withheld until relatives
could be notified, said Vance spokesman Kent Cummins.
</P>
<P>
The T-37 is the standard U.S. Air Force jet trainer, a twin-
engine craft used for pilot and navigator instruction.
</P>
<P>
Vance is home of the 71st Flying Training Wing, which trains
pilots for the U.S. Air Force, Navy, Marines, Air National Guard,
Air Force Reserves and allied countries, officials said.
</P>
<P>
This is the third similar aircraft crash within a week.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday a military jet crashed in the San Antonio area.
The pilot and co-pilot ejected before impact and were receiving
medical attention.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, a New Jersey Air National Guard F-16 fighter
jet crashed off the coast of Atlantic City. The pilot ejected
safely and has been rescued by a New Jersey State Police boat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
