<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Suffers Brain Drain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand is suffering a
brain drain with many skilled young people leaving for foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
During the period from July 1999 to June 2000, 71,045 people,
including a lot of young ones, left for overseas, registering a
net migration loss of 9,760, according to figures issued by
Statistics New Zealand here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The capital city of Wellington is the biggest victim of New
Zealand's brain drain, losing more young professionals to jobs
overseas than any other centers.
</P>
<P>
It lost 8,360 people overseas in the year with 5,000 of them
aged under 30. The capital city had a net migration loss of 3,076.
</P>
<P>
Though Wellington accounts for only 9 percent of the national
population, it makes up 32 percent of the net migration loss.
</P>
<P>
It is said Wellingtonians are better educated and would find it
easier to get work overseas.
</P>
<P>
Christchurch, the biggest city on South Island, has the same
problem as Wellington. It suffered a net migration loss of 1,831
during the year.
</P>
<P>
Australia is the biggest benefactor, with 36,296 crossing the
Tasman.
</P>
<P>
The economic slump and low salaries are the main reasons for
many skilled young people to leave New Zealand for foreign
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
