<HEADLINE> New Zealanders Advised to Defer Travel to Solomon Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- New Zealanders are advised
to defer all non-essential travel to the Solomon Islands.
</P>
<P>
The advice was contained in a notice issued here Thursday by
the New Zealand Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade.
</P>
<P>
The notice said the security situation in the Solomon Islands
remains"unstable."
</P>
<P>
"A cease-fire agreement between rival militant groups was
signed on August 3, but has been breached on a number of occasions.
Initial peace talks are scheduled to begin on September 7.
Grievances which gave rise to the crisis are yet to be resolved,"
it said.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, the notice added, there have been occasional
clashes between militant groups and instances of lawless acts.
</P>
<P>
Although expatriates have not generally been targeted, they
have been caught up in some incidents, it said.
</P>
<P>
The notice urged New Zealanders in the Solomon Islands to
register with the New Zealand High Commission in Honiara if they
have not already done so. 
</P>
</TEXT>
