<HEADLINE> New Zealand Dollar Hits All-Time Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand dollar took
a dive to another all-time low Thursday afternoon, reaching 41.88
U.S. cents, according to Television New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The fall below 42 U.S. cents was brief as the local currency
soon rebounded to around the 42 U.S. cent mark.
</P>
<P>
The fall of the New Zealand dollar was triggered by a weakened
Australian dollar, which in turn was sideswiped by the weak euro.
</P>
<P>
Local economic analysts were quoted as saying the loss was also
prompted by New Zealand's continuing large merchandise trade
deficit of 3.1 billion NZ dollars for the year from August 1999 to
July 2000.
</P>
<P>
The annual trade deficit was made public here Thursday by the
government statistical organ, Statistics New Zealand. 
