<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MANILA Tries to Keep Food Prices Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Following the latest oil price
hike and the depreciation of the peso, the Philippine government
said Thursday that it is doing everything possible to keep food
prices stable.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Secretary Edgardo Angara said in a radio interview
that food takes up the biggest chunk of the ordinary Filipinos'
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
"We are doing everything to stabilize the prices of food items.
We can not prevent a price hike because of the price increase in
oil and the fall of the peso," Angara said.
</P>
<P>
He also said he would propose to President Joseph Estrada the
return of the Food Terminal Inc. (FTI) under the Agriculture
Department so it can play a more active role in food security.
</P>
<P>
According to Angara, the FTI has cold storage facilities that
would keep vegetable supply from the provinces fresh or at least
prevent them from spoiling early.
</P>
<P>
"The FTI was removed from the Agriculture Department when we
could have played a key role in food production. Perhaps, I would
recommend to the president that we reconnect the FTI and the
department. The FTI has good storage facilities," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said the Agriculture Department is planning to
establish a"cold chain system" similar to the one in Japan, where
producers bring their vegetables to a central area.
</P>
<P>
Angara said the fall of the peso and the hike in oil prices
have also jacked up the prices of diesel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
