<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Replaces Montana As Focus Of U.S. Wildfires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Drought-stricken Texas has
replaced Montana as the focus of wildfires in the United States,
according to press reports here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here say there are presently 35 wildfires
burning in Texas, 24 in Montana, 19 in Idaho and two in Wyoming.
Other states including Nevada, New Mexico, South Dakota, Arkansas,
California and Mississippi were reported to have only one fire
each.
</P>
<P>
While most of the fires are small compared with the giant
blazes still burning in the northern Rocky mountains, some of the
Texas fires have destroyed homes, are threatening towns and
forcing evacuations, firefighters said.
</P>
<P>
A 5,000-acre fire north of Beaumont jumped a highway and
destroyed several structures, according to the National
Interagency Fire Center in Boise, Texas. It said the town of
Newton is threatened and evacuations are occurring.
</P>
<P>
A blaze west of San Antonio is keeping about 250 people out of
their homes.
</P>
<P>
In New Caney, north of Houston, about 100 residents were
evacuated to a middle school until a 300-acre fire was contained.
</P>
<P>
Crews from Georgia, South Carolina, and Florida are helping
battle fires in Texas where 180,627 acres have burned so far this
year, compared with 1,241,290 acres in Idaho and 935,699 acres in
Montana.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, wildfires throughout the United States have
burned 6,602,499 acres, the fire center said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Although some fire-danger restrictions remain in place in
Montana, the focus of U.S. fires during the past two months, road
barriers and land-closure signs came down Tuesday as millions of
acres of land were reopened to hikers and other outdoors
enthusiasts as cooler weather helped firefighters get the upper
hand on some blazes.
</P>
<P>
Similar conditions in Idaho have enabled officials to reopen
more than 2 million acres of land that had been closed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
