<HEADLINE> California Bank Robber Surrenders, Releases Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A gunman surrendered to
police Wednesday afternoon following a foiled robbery and hostage
situation at a bank in the Orange County, California. No injuries
were reported from the incident.
</P>
<P>
The drama came to a close shortly after 2 p.m. local time, when
the gunman lay face down in a parking lot and police arrested him.
</P>
<P>
Officer Robin Kapp, a spokesman for the Westminster Police
Department, said someone in the bank called police, and the silent
alarm was also activated. Officers responded to the scene.
</P>
<P>
"Apparently, the suspect saw the officers, and that's when the
suspect took the hostages," Kapp said.
</P>
<P>
Kapp said the gunman released 12 hostages almost immediately
after the incident began. Two hours into the drama, another five
hostages were seen leaving the bank, and the gunman surrendered
shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
Kapp said none of the hostages were injured by the gunman. But
he said that someone at the scene collapsed and required medical
attention.
</P>
<P>
During the two-hour siege, the gunman fired one shot into the
ceiling, but it didn't appear anyone was seriously hurt in the
takeover, Kapp said.
</P>
<P>
Helicopter images of the siege at the Orange County bank, 60
kilometers southeast of Los Angeles, were shown nationally on
television.
</P>
<P>
The gunman, described as an Asian in his 30s, stormed into the
Bank of America at about noon with a TEC-9 handgun and claimed to
have a bomb in a backpack or bag that he carried with him.
</P>
<P>
A bomb squad was then summoned to search the bank for explosive
devices.  
</P>
</TEXT>
