<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM: G-77 Decision-Making "Bulky, Unwieldy" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Thursday described the decision-making process of
the G-77 as "bulky and unwieldy".
</P>
<P>
"In the G-77, everything must be done through consensus by the
130 heads of government. Obviously it is bulky and unwieldy," he
told a news conference at the Kuala Lumpur International Airport
in Sepang on his return from a three-day working visit to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir proposed that the G-77 consider delegating certain
tasks to a smaller number of heads of government to make the
grouping more effective.
</P>
<P>
He however said he doubted this would happen as G-77 leaders
preferred to discuss every matter among themselves.
</P>
<P>
"Of course if they want to (participate), it's okay by us but I
don't think it's practically going to work at all," Mahathir who
attended a special G-77 summit in New York said.
</P>
<P>
The G-77 is a grouping of developing countries of the South.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said compared to the G-8 which groups the world's most
developed countries, it was more difficult for the G-77 to conduct
meetings due to the size of the grouping.
</P>
<P>
He said that the only time that the views of the G-77 could be
put across to the G-8 was after the convening of the G-77 summit
meeting in Havana last April.
</P>
<P>
"Even then, they (G-77) did not meet the G-8 heads of
government because they (G-8) did not think they should consider
the views of the South at all," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to the United States, Mahathir received the
Lariba Lifetime Achievement Award 2000 from the American-based
Islamic financial house in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir was the first ever recipient of the award, conferred
on an international leader for outstanding contributions to the
development of the Muslim world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
