<HEADLINE> Thailand Urges Laos to Withdraw From Border Islets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Thailand on Thursday urged
Laos to withdraw its militia from three yet-to-be-demarcated small
islets in the border river of Mekong.
</P>
<P>
The islets, situated in the Mekong river between Thai Chiangrai
province, 785 north of Bangkok, and the northern Lao province of
Bokeo, should left untouched until the border is properly
demarcated, said an announcement from the Thai Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Thai provincial officials said that a group of over 30 Lao
militiamen have been deployed in the Koh Mano 1, Koh Mano 2 and
Koh Phakham islets since last week, where Thai villagers grow corn
in the dry season, but abandon them in the flooding season.
</P>
<P>
Thai authorities have ordered the villagers to stop using these
islets to prevent any future dispute, the Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
To seek the opinions from the Lao side, it said Chiang Rai
Governor Samreng Boonyopakorn will meet his Lao counterpart of
Bokeo Friday to discuss the problem.
</P>
<P>
Also, Lao Ambassador to Thailand Hiem Phommachan will soon be
summoned to Thai Foreign Ministry for this issue, it added.
</P>
<P>
Thailand and Lao have agreed to demarcate their river boundary
after their land border is properly marked. The two countries
share 702 kilometers land frontier and 398 kilometers river border,
and 65 percent of the land border have been demarcated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
