<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Drops One Place in Global Competitive Stakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The newspaper quoted the Swiss-based forum's Global
Competitiveness Report 2000 as saying Thailand's competitiveness
has fallen one place to 31st this year among the 59 economies
under the survey.
</P>
<P>
The United States is ranked as the world's most competitive
nation, advancing from second place last year due largely to major
advances in technological development. It is followed by Singapore,
Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Ireland, Finland, Canada, Hong Kong,
the United Kingdom and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The survey, measuring the conditions that determine a nation's
sustainable level of productivity, found that Thailand still has a
long way to go in enhancing its competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
In product design, scientific research, technology and private
spending on research and development, Thailand is ranked 56th,
54th, 52nd and 45th respectively. Its banking system is ranked
56th, almost at the bottom, while the supervision of the banking
system is ranked 53rd.
</P>
<P>
But the survey scores Thailand highly on its openness,
particularly the exchange rate alignment and export promotion
which are ranked 9th and 13th respectively.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's access to external finance is also very open, ranked
at second place. The national saving rate is also high at 6th
place, while the investment rate is 10th.
</P>
<P>
In economic creativity, Thailand is ranked 40th, with
innovation at 50th, technology transfer at 36th and start-ups at
32nd.
</P>
<P>
All other Asian economies, except India, also dropped in
ranking this year.
</P>
<P>
The survey is useful for countries to understand the factors
that contribute to future growth of their economies, measured as
the rate of change of the gross domestic product per person. These
factors explain why some countries are improving their prosperity
faster than others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
