<HEADLINE> UNHCR Workers Evacuated From Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations force in
East Timor has safely evacuated 54 humanitarian workers from
Atambua, a city of Indonesia's East Nusa Tenggara province, where
four U.N. staff were killed Wednesday in an attack on the office
of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) by East Timor
militiamen.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. force sent four helicopters from East Timor town of
Suai to Atambua immediately after the attack occurred. As of 8:00
p.m., the U.N. staff in Atambua had been evacuated to Dili,
capital of East Timor, while some others were being located to the
East Nusa Tenggara provincial capital of Kupang and other parts of
Indonesia, the Jakarta Post daily Thursday quoted the U.N. office
in Jakarta as saying.
</P>
<P>
Four U.N. staff were killed and one badly injured when
thousands of angry mobs and militiamen attacked and burned the
UNHCR office Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said militiamen beat four foreign U.N. workers to
death and burned their bodies in the street.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. building was also set on fire by the mob angered by
the unsolved death a day earlier of a prominent militia leader,
accused of committing atrocities in East Timor last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jake Morland, UNHCR spokesman in Kupang, said 90
UNHCR staffers elsewhere in the province were on the standby for
possible evacuation in case the violence spread.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. agency has been delivered aid to an estimated 90,000
refugees who have lingered in border in camps after fleeing
violence in East Timor 12 months ago.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday night in Atambua, Udayana military Commander Kiki
Syahnakri met with UNHCR officials, police representatives and
local administration officials. After the meeting, he said a joint
team would be formed to investigate the death of U.N. workers and
to secure the remaining staff in Kupang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
