<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Audit State Administrators' Wealth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A Commission for Auditing the
Wealth of State Administrators (KPKPN) was established in
Indonesia on Wednesday according to a presidential decree signed
on September 2, the Indonesian Observer daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
KPKPN Secretary General Amir Muin said the commission will
audit the wealth of top state officials assets and business
dealings of officials including President Abdurrahman Wahid and
Vice President Megawati Soekarnoputri.
</P>
<P>
After the central government, he said, the commission will
audit the wealth of governors, regents and military officials.
Then it will audit the speakers of the House of Representatives
and People's Consultative Assembly, as well as Supreme court
officials, judges, prosecutors and police.
</P>
<P>
The state officials will have to list their official income and
additional sources of income, as well as any money or assets
received from relatives and associate, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"If the sum is considered irrational, the commission has the
authority to make a further investigation and convey the results
to the relevant institutions," said Muin.
</P>
<P>
The commission has 25 members and is divided into four
subcommissions, each of which will deal with a specific sector of
state institutions: executive, legislative, judicial and state
enterprises.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
