<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Pension Market Projected to Reach $12 Trillion by 2030 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Asia, with nearly 3
trillion U.S. dollars invested in pension funds, has become one of
the most important pension fund markets in the world, according to
a report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Now equivalent to one quarter of the U.S. pension fund market,
the Asian pension market is projected to continue to increase by 6
percent annually to reach 12 trillion U.S. dollars by the year
2030, said the report from the U.S.-based Nelson Information, a
division of Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
The five fastest growing countries within this market are
expected to be China with a 44 percent annual growth, Indonesia,
the Philippines, India and Malaysia. The World Bank expects the
Japanese and Chinese markets to exceed 8 trillion U.S. dollars by
2030, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Japan, with 2.2 trillion U.S. dollars invested in pension funds,
accounts for 81 percent of the region's total.
</P>
<P>
Even though pension fund asset allocations in Asia show
relatively low weighting to international equities, substantial
flows toward foreign investment management companies should occur
as investment restrictions are removed, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Program Planned for Refurbishing Yuanmingyuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts have approved
of a plan to refurbish the ruins in Yuanmingyuan Park in Beijing,
according to the latest weekly of Beijing Review.
</P>
<P>
The reconstruction of the park will be aimed at protecting its
present conditions, rather than reverting to the "prosperity of
old days".
</P>
<P>
The program focuses on proper utilization and protection in a
scientific way with following measures:
</P>
<P>
-- Removing the residents, work units and amusement facilities
inside the ruins which do not comply with the surrounding ambience;
</P>
<P>
-- Cleaning up and rearranging the whole site with protective
measures;
</P>
<P>
-- Recovering the original outline of hills and water system
and planting vegetation;
</P>
<P>
-- Rebuilding paths, bridges, pavilions, terraces, open halls
and arch gates at the entrance to the park and to Changchunyuan,
as well as the "Hanjin Hall" which will house historic relics of
Yuanmingyuan.
</P>
<P>
Yuanmingyuan, located in west Beijing in an area traditionally
home to parks and gardens, was one of the most outstanding parks
in the world 140 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Emperors of several generations lived and handled the country's
affairs in the park with numerous gems, cultural relics and books
for the imperial family.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, the park, covering 350 ha, was looted and burned
by the British and French imperialists in 1860, and then further
destroyed by the allied army of eight imperialist countries at the
end of the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
The park was formally renamed as "Yuanmingyuan Ruins Park" in
early 1983.
</P>
<P>
Wu Shuqin, senior engineer of the Beijing Research and Design
Institute for Urban Planning, said that the scenic area of Xiyang
Building, the typical architecture of Yuanmingyuan when it existed,
will not be rebuilt on a large scale.
</P>
<P>
Wu, taking charge of the new Yuanmingyuan program, added that
other destroyed buildings will just be renovated for protection,
not totally refurbished in every aspect.
</P>
<P>
The Yuanmingyuan site is composed of three parks: Yuanmingyuan,
Changchunyuan and Wanchunyuan and the redeveloped Yuanmingyuan
Ruins Park will cover an area of 4,589 ha.
</P>
<P>
It will have two sections: One is the ruins of the three old
parks, where no new architecture of scenic works will be built.
</P>
<P>
The other is the newly added 100-ha areas surrounding the ruins.
It will contain gardens and service trade buildings.
</P>
<P>
The height and color of the buildings to be built are required
to comply with the ambience of Yuanmingyuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
