<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia's Revenue Up in First Semester </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 7 (Xinhua) -- More revenue was collected
by the Cambodian government during the first six months of this
year, but nearly half of the country's domestic budget is still
being spent on security and defense, Finance Minister Keat Chhon
was quoted by local newspapers Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
"In terms of expenditure, spending on health, education,
agriculture and rural development was slow. But it will be caught
up in the second semester," Keat Chhon said.
</P>
<P>
According to Ministry of Finance figures, the government
generated 184 million U.S. dollars through tax revenue and other
fees between January and June -- slightly less than the target for
that time period, but up 5.4 percent from the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Tax revenue reached 137 million, or 74 percent of the total
current revenue in the first six months while value added tax -- a
10 percent tax imposed on services and goods generated 50 million,
making a 5.6 million leap from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
But revenue from customs duties declined 12 percent from 59.7
million in 1999 to 52.9 million in the same period this year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 611.7 million has been budgeted for Cambodia during
the year 2000, but only 390.9 million is raised domestically. The
remainder comes from the international community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
