<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Trafficker Involved in Illegal Arms Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- An international arms trafficker
may be involved in the illegal sale of weapons to the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC) guerrillas, said two
Peruvian military officers to the La Republica newspaper Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sarkis Soghanalian, a 60-year-old Lebanese, supervised the
shipment of 10,000 rifles from the Jordanian capital of Amman last
year; it is believed the weapons were sent to FARC, Peruvian army
technicians Santos Cenepo Shapiama and Luis Alberto Meza were
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The officers affirmed that the Lebanese trafficker was in the
Peruvian capital in the first few weeks of 1999 to coordinate the
shipment of arms with his Peruvian partners. The arms were
reportedly bought in Jordan and then transported to the Colombian
jungle in Illyusin-76 planes piloted by Ukrainian crews.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian authorities have investigated this case of arms
trafficking, and former Peruvian Army lieutenant Luis Aybar Cancho,
now working with FARC, was supposedly a leader of the gang
involved.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian military judicial authorities in charge of the
investigation have so far discovered the alleged participation of
33 persons, among them civilians and former members of the
Peruvian Armed Forces who allegedly forged official documents to
acquire the weapons, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
