<HEADLINE> Mexico to Sell Bonds in Japanese Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Mexico will issue 50
billion yen (475 million U.S. dollars) in bonds in the Japanese
market. It will be the second of its kind this year and the third
since November 1999, the Mexican government announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Funds obtained from the documents will be earmarked for the
advanced payment of debts in yen, which will result in savings for
the service of the country's foreign debt, the Finance Ministry
said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
With a 2.25 percent yearly interest in yen -- the Japanese
currency -- the bonds, will be reimbursed in four years. They will
be placed by the Daiwa SBCM financial company, the ministry said.
</P>
