<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adopts Environment-Friendly Way to Dispose Rubbish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- China is adopting an
environment-friendly way of rubbish disposal by building its
largest rubbish-burning fueled power plant in Shanghai, China
Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The plant to be built in Shanghai's Pudong New District is
designed to have the capacity to generate 100,000 megawatts of
electricity annually by means of thermal energy generated through
burning 365,000 tons of rubbish, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The project, expected to be completed in October 2001, will
cost 670 million yuan (80.7 million U.S. dollars), including a low-
interest loan of 30.17 million offered by the French government.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the loan will be used to buy some key
technology and equipment from France for the new power plant, an
official surnamed Tao who is responsible for the construction of
the plant and the installation of the equipment was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The plant will keep a close eye on the discharge of waste gas
and smoke and fume emissions in accordance with the emission
standards set by the European Union, said the official, adding
that the new plant will become a pilot project for neighboring
areas of Shanghai and other big cities in terms of rubbish
disposal.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai now yields more than 10,000 tons of household waste
every day, of which about 80 percent is buried after a fermenting
procedure to decrease harmful elements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Puts Natural Gas for Bidding  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan state oil company
Petroleos de Venezuela (PDVSA) announced Wednesday the start of
the bidding process for 11 areas for exploration and exploitation
of non associate natural gas deposits.
</P>
<P>
The bidding is open for foreign firms. The company vice
president Domingo Marsicobetre said that investments of one
billion dollars are foreseen for the next 20 years in these 11
areas distributed in the country's territory that contain energy
equivalent to around three billion barrels of oil.
</P>
<P>
The conditions for the licencings include the exclusive
participation of private investors at their own risk and cost,
rights over the production, licencing for 35 years of exploitation
that can be extended for 30 more years of free marketing right.
</P>
<P>
According to this plan, natural gas could supply 54 percent of
the Venezuelan demand of energy by the year 2010, against 42
percent it provides in 2000. In barrels terms, it means to go from
the present one million barrels per day (bpd) to 1.67 million bpd
in 2010.
</P>
<P>
It was known that the registration will start on September 7
and the biddings will be presented from October to January, which
will be decided upon in the last month of 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
