<HEADLINE> U.S. Backs Foreign Credit for Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States Treasury
Department has agreed to support Colombia for the acquisition of
foreign resources of at least 1.2 billion dollars, Colombian
Finance Minister Juan Manuel Santos said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The operation will be carried out in the first days of next
year with the floating of bonds that will be backed by the World
Bank and the Inter-American Development Bank, said Santos.
</P>
<P>
Colombia faces obstacles to entry into the international money
markets because of a lack of confidence in the economy of the
country and its internal political situation, according to
financial experts.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister said that the credit is one of the first
results of contacts with the U.S. economic authorities.
</P>
<P>
He said that the obtaining of foreign resources will need a
reduction of the budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Minister met Tuesday with U.S. Treasury Secetary
Lawrence Summers, who offered full support to the adjustment plan
and asked the international financial community to restablish its
confidence in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Santos also met with the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
executives that will decide on Thursday on the performance of the
Colombian economy, as well as with the fulfillment of the
commitments and the adjustment targets.
</P>
<P>
Bank of the Republic manager MIguel Urrutia Montoya said that
Colombia will not have problems for a good rating by the IMF,
because it fulfilled its budget and monetary commitments, and
strengthened its international reserves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
