<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhuhai to Be Urbanized Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHUHAI, September 7 (Xinhua) --Authorities of Zhuhai, south
China's Guangdong Province, have pledged to make greater efforts
to further urbanize the city in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the city's pre-set goal of realizing
modernization by the year 2007, Zhuhai's urbanization level will
be at 87 percent, said Mayor Huang Longyun.
</P>
<P>
According to Huang, the per capita gross domestic product (GDP)
of the city will reach 5,050 U.S. dollars by 2007, and the output
value of high-tech products will make up 28 percent of the city's
total industrial output value.
</P>
<P>
Zhuhai, the nearest Chinese mainland city to Macao, is also one
of China's four earliest special economic zones (SEZ). It
celebrated the 20th anniversary of its founding late last month.
</P>
<P>
In the past two decades, Zhuhai has experienced an annual
economic growth rate of 24 percent. It has grown from a tiny
fishing village into a bustling seaside city with sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Zhuhai was cited by the U.N. Center for Human
Settlements (Habitat) as a model city in the world for
comprehensive environmental management amid rapid urban growth. It
has been chosen as the venue for China International Air Show, a
biennial event, and for international (Formula) motor racing.
</P>
<P>
Zhuhai now has an urban population of over 400,000. The fine
urban environment and its special geographic position have turned
the city into a popular site for investments among overseas
investors. It is now home to over 3,000 overseas-financed
businesses, including those run by multinationals such as Amoco,
Iwatani and Seibu of Japan. By the end of 1999, a total of 7.75
billion U.S. dollars of overseas capital had been invested into
the city.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Huang said that they have been concentrating efforts to
build the city into five functional zones since the beginning of
the year.
</P>
<P>
The five zones are: the state high-tech industrial development
zone, bonded zone for foreign trade, industrial zone adjacent to
the port, Wanshan experimental zone for marine development, and
Hengqin development zone for international tourism, holiday makers
and theme parks.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investment has kept flowing into the five zones. By
late June, 83 overseas-financed projects have been approved to be
built in the zones, involving 218 million U.S. dollars of foreign
direct investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
