<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S House Fails to Override Clinton Veto of Estate Tax Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives failed Thursday to override President Bill Clinton
's veto of a bill repealing estate taxes, leaving the issue for
Republicans and Democrats to argue about in the fall election
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
By a 274-157 vote, the Republican-controlled House fell 14
short of the necessary two-thirds margin of those voting to
override the veto of a bill, which was estimated to cost 105
billion U.S. dollars as it gradually phased out the tax over 10
years.
</P>
<P>
Even though a clear House majority favored repeal and polls
show many Americans believe the tax is unfair, Democrats said just
as many people want Congress to focus on paying down public debt,
education and creating a Medicare prescription drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
Democrats also portrayed the bill as a giveaway to wealthy
families and only one part of a huge tax cut proposed by the
Republicans that would consume too much of the projected budget
surplus.
</P>
<P>
The first 675,000 U.S. dollars of an estate is exempt from a
tax that reaches 55 percent, meaning only about 2 percent of
estates are affected each year. But the issue gained steam on
Capitol Hill this year amid a forceful lobbying campaign led by
the National Association of Manufacturers, American Farm Bureau
Federation and National Federation of Independent Business.
</P>
<P>
There have been nine previous attempts by Congress to override
a Clinton veto since Republicans took power in 1995. Four have won
House approval and only two, on budget line-item vetoes and
securities litigation reform, were overridden by the House and
Senate as required. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000907.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Urges U.N. to Reflect Will of All Peoples </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Iraq said Thursday that
the United Nations should reflect the will of all member states so
as to be successful in countering challenges of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Millennium Summit which opened at the U.N.
headquarters in New York Wednesday, Tariq Aziz, deputy prime
minister of Iraq, said provisions of the U.N. Charter have
stipulated that the interest sought is common and collective
interest.
</P>
<P>
However, the most important fact of the past era was that the
ability to properly apply the provisions of the U.N. Charter is
not often possible due to the influences of the powerful states
that dominate international resolutions for their own interests,
the deputy prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
"This situation was aggravated during the 1990s as a result of
the U.S. hegemony and domination on the international organization
for the benefit of its imperialist objectives," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
"Thus, the work of the United Nations in the 21st century
should be directed first towards resuming the proper application
of the charter and the prevention of hegemony on the U.N.
resolutions and positions," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
The essential step in this move is to reform the decision-
making structures in the United Nations, particularly the Security
Council, so that it could really reflect the will of all member
states, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ironically, the United Nations, whose charter provided for the
protection of human rights, accepted to be a tool to violate the
fundamental human rights through the comprehensive and
unrestricted use of sanctions albeit the sufferings those
sanctions inflict upon the targeted people, he noted.
</P>
<P>
In the case of Iraq, the Iraqi victims of these unjust and
unrestricted sanctions amounted to more than 1 million of children,
women and elderly people during the past 10 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is not enough to only admit that sanctions are an inactive
tool that leads to counterproductive results and the use of
sanctions should be restricted and they should not trespass the
scope of the U.N. Charter, he noted.
</P>
<P>
They also should not be a hostage, as in the case of Iraq, of
the will of the United States of America which hijacked the
resolution on the lifting of sanctions on Iraq from the Security
Council in the service of its own interest and hostile politics,
Aziz added.
</P>
<P>
The deputy prime minister said Iraq cautiously and dubiously
looks at the so-called humanitarian intervention since this call
may be used, and it has been actually used to interfere in the
internal affairs of other states by the influential states,
particularly the United States, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
