<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Won't Confirm Paratroops Moving to S.Leone: MoD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Britain Thursday declined to
comment on a report that a number of British paratroops had
arrived in Sierra Leone in an effort to free the six British
soldiers taken hostage by renegade militiamen in that Western
African country.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Defense (MoD) said it did not discuss
individual troop movements.
</P>
<P>
"Any movements are on a contingency basis so we're ready to
respond to any contingencies that might arise," a Reuters report
quoted an MoD spokesman as saying in London.
</P>
<P>
The BBC said on its website that reliable sources in Freetown,
capital of Sierra Leone, had confirmed the arrival of fresh
British forces, including some with the distinctive red berets of
the paratroops who had been dispatched to Senegal Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The key thing is that any movements don't imply any worsening
or any developments in the situation one way or the other. Our
priority remains to secure a peaceful resolution," the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
Eleven British soldiers, who were training a new Sierra Leonean
government army, were abducted by a band of former Sierra Leonean
troops called the West Side Boys on August 25.
</P>
<P>
The group freed five of them on August 30 after Britain agreed
to give them some military equipment and food.
</P>
<P>
The MoD spokesman said negotiations with the West Side Boys were
continuing.
</P>
<P>
"We're not commenting on any detail of any discussion. It wouldn
't be helpful in terms of what we're aiming to achieve," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
