<HEADLINE> Myanmar Says Not to Bow to Criticism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar said on
Thursday that it will not bow to harsh criticism at the United
Nations over its human rights record and pledged to purse its own
path of development without harming anyone or committing
atrocities.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the three-day Millennium Summit which opened at the
U.N. headquarters in New York Wednesday, Foreign Minister U Win
Aung said the Myanmar government was taking a constructive path
while opposing forces that were embarking on a path to destruction.
</P>
<P>
"There is no single formula that could be applied to all
countries. It would be wrong for powerful countries to impose
their systems on others," the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
"In this context, let me once again reiterate that Myanmar is
building a genuine and durable democratic system in our own way
and yet there are some who would like to stir up the tranquil
waters," the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
Several world leaders at the summit criticized Myanmar for its
treatment of opposition leader Aung San Suu kyi. 
</P>
