<HEADLINE> Bush Presses for Military Modernization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Republican
presidential candidate George W. Bush focused on defense issues
for the second day Thursday, vowing to prepare the armed forces
for "Information Age battles."
</P>
<P>
In a speech in Dayton, Ohio, Texas Governor Bush promised a "
culture of innovation" in modernizing the military through
investment in technology.
</P>
<P>
Bush, who was accompanied by retired generals Colin Powell and
Norman Schwarzkopf, accused the Clinton administration of lagging
in "protecting ourselves and our allies from the new threats in
the world."
</P>
<P>
"I will have a culture of innovation," Bush said, adding that
if elected he would assign a task force to decide "how best to
spend our resources to redefine how war is fought and won."
</P>
<P>
Bush's running mate, Dick Cheney, was also campaigning on
military modernization Thursday in South Portland, Maine.
</P>
<P>
The Texas governor Thursday described himself as the underdog
in the presidential race and pledged to change his campaign style
and strategy to revitalize his White House bid.
</P>
<P>
Bush, who was criticized by the local press for rejecting
presidential debates sponsored by the bipartisan Commission on
Presidential Debates, also appeared to reposition himself on the
debate issue.
</P>
<P>
"There will be debates, but what they look like and where they
are will be worked out in due course," he told reporters during a
campaign stop in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Democratic presidential nominee Al Gore continued
his focus on economic issues Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"What I am hearing is that the American people want to continue
our prosperity, but do even better," Gore said during a campaign
visit to Carbondale, Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated his proposals to balance the budget, pay off the
national debt, as well as secure social security and Medicare.
</P>
