<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interpol Requests Eliminating Drug Trafficker's Bank Secrecy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 7 (Xinhua) -- International Police (
Interpol) asked Thursday for the elimination of banking secrecy of
drug traffickers, who earn yearly nearly 500 billion U.S. dollars
all over the world, within framework of the Sixth Cocaine Traffic
World Conference being held in Acapulco, southern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Director of the Interpol Drug Unit Jean Michel Louboutin said
his organization backs up initiatives to eliminate banking secrecy
to combat these illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
He said at a press conference that it's necessary to fight
criminal gangs that carry out financial operations with means
coming from drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
In 1999 and at the beginning of year 2000, Interpol made a "
black list" of countries considered as "laundry" centers so that
other nations can investigate suspects better.
</P>
<P>
Louboutin said that Interpol is the first organization that has
created a permanent group of specialists and experts against
corruption in all aspects, but as this phenomenon is underground,
it's not easy to detect.
</P>
<P>
The Sixth World Conference on Cocaine Trafficking opened
Wednesday in the Mexican tourist port of Acapulco, 250 kilometers
south of Mexico City, with the attendance of delegates from 178
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
