<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Africa Urges Will From World Leaders to Eradicate Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Addressing the three-day Millennium Summit which opened at the
U.N. headquarters in New York, Thabo Mbeki, president of South
Africa, said the fundamental challenge that faces this summit is
that in a credible wary, the world leaders must show the will.
</P>
<P>
"We have to ensure that the poor play their role, not as
recipients of largesse and goodwill, but as co-determinants of
what happens to the common universe of which they are an important
part," Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
"The essential question we have to answer at this summit is
whether we have the courage and the conscience to demonstrate that
we have the will to ensure that we permit no situation that will
deny any human community its dignity," the president said.
</P>
<P>
"Part of the naked truth is that the second millennium provided
humanity with the capital, technology and human skills to end
poverty and underdevelopment throughout the world," Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
"Another part of that truth is that we have refused to use this
enormous capacity to end the contemporary, deliberate and savage
violence of poverty and underdevelopment," he said,
</P>
<P>
The summit should create the conditions to end this trend, the
president added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
