<HEADLINE> Soprano Reaches Out of Court Settlement of Voice Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Julie Andrews, star of "
The Sound of Music," said Thursday that she has reached a
settlement of the medical malpractice lawsuit she filed relating
to a voice surgery.
</P>
<P>
In a brief statement issued from both home here and New York,
the actress said she has settled this case "in a favorable manner"
and felt glad "to close this chapter on an event which is
unfortunate for all concerned." She also thanked her attorneys,
but did not disclose the terms of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
The British-born actress underwent a throat operation in 1997
in New York's Mt. Sinai Hospital to remove noncancerous throat
nodules. She was hoping the surgery would expedite her return to
the stage, but it resulted in her total disability of singing
again. In the lawsuit against the hospital and two doctors in
December 1999, she claimed that the operation was botched, leaving
her with hoarseness, permanent vocal chord damage and other
complications.
</P>
<P>
Andrews won her fame in the movie musicals of the 1960 such as
"The Sound of Music" and "My Fair Lady." She won her Oscar with "
Mary Poppins." 
</P>
</TEXT>
